# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: united-kingdom
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] On 15 February 2003, a coordinated day of protests was held across the world in which people in more than 600 cities expressed opposition to the imminent Iraq War.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] It was part of a series of protests and political events that had begun in 2002 and continued as the invasion, war, and occupation took place.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The day was described by social movement researchers as "the largest protest event in human history".
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] According to BBC News, between six and ten million people took part in protests in up to sixty countries over the weekend of 15 and 16 February.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The largest protests took place in Europe.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The one in Rome involved around three million people, and is listed in the 2004 *Guinness Book of World Records* as the largest anti-war rally in history.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Madrid hosted the second largest rally with more than 1.5 million people protesting against the invasion of Iraq.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Beijing, three smaller protests were held the following day, attended by foreigners and domestic students.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In 2002, the United States government began to argue for the necessity of invading Iraq.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] This formally began with a speech by US President George W.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Bush to the United Nations General Assembly on 12 September 2002 which argued that the Iraqi government of Saddam Hussein was violating United Nations (UN) resolutions, primarily on weapons of mass destruction, and that this necessitated action.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The proposed war was controversial with many people questioning the motives of the US government and its rationale.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] One poll which covered 41 countries claimed that less than 10% would support an invasion of Iraq without UN sanction and that half would not support an invasion under any circumstances.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Anti-war groups worldwide organised public protests.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] According to the French academic Dominique Reynié, between 3 January and 12 April 2003, 36 million people across the globe took part in almost 3,000 anti‑war protests, the demonstrations on 15 February 2003 being the largest and most prolific.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The 15 February international protests were unprecedented not only in terms of the size of the demonstrations but also in terms of the international coordination involved.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Immanuel Wallerstein has spoken of the international protests as being organised by the forces of "the camps of Porto Alegre and Davos" in reference to the emergence of global social movements who had been organising around international events such as the 2001 World Social Forum in Porto Alegre.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The idea for an international day of demonstrations was first raised by the British anti-capitalist group Globalise Resistance (GR) in the wake of an anti-war demonstration in Britain of 400,000 on 28 September.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] At the time GR was involved in planning for the Florence European Social Forum (ESF) and brought up the suggestion at an ESF planning meeting.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] According to GR's Chris Nineham, "There was considerable controversy.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Some delegates were worried it would alienate the mainstream of the movement.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The proposal was accepted and at the final rally of the ESF, in November 2002, the call officially went out for Europe-wide demonstrations on 15 February 2003.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] This call was firmed up in December at a planning meeting for the following ESF which took place in Copenhagen in 2003.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] This meeting was attended by delegates from many European anti-war organisations, the US group United for Peace and Justice, and representatives of groups from the Philippines.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The decision was taken to set up a Europe-wide anti-war website and to commit to spreading organisational coordination both within and beyond Europe.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] An email network connecting the different national organisations across Europe, and eventually also the different US groups, was set up.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In December 2002, the Cairo Anti-war Conference pledged to organize demonstrations in Egypt and the International Campaign Against Aggression on Iraq (which came out of the Cairo conference) sought to co-ordinate more demonstrations across the world.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Around this time, the US anti-war group International ANSWER called for actions in North America supporting the proposed protests in Europe.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Another important platform for the spreading call to demonstrate internationally occurred at the World Social Forum in Porto Alegre, Brazil which took place at the end of 2002.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] European delegates sought to popularize the plan for the increasingly international demonstration.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] They met with some success, including the organisation of an anti‑war assembly which was attended by almost 1,000 people.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The song "Boom!", by System of a Down, had a music video filmed on the day of the protest, showing the many protest locations and people's opinions on the Iraq War.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Demonstrations took place across Europe and some of the largest drawing attendance figures in the tens of thousands in many cities.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Approximately one-fifth of the total demonstrators worldwide protested in Europe.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Austria, 30,000 people (SW estimate) took to the streets of its capital, Vienna.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Switzerland in order to "concentrate the movement" most activists agreed to organise a single demonstration for the whole country in Bern.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] On the day roughly 40,000 people joined the protest in front of the Bundeshaus, the seat of the Swiss federal government and parliament.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The demonstration, which ran under the slogan **Nein zum Krieg gegen Irak – Kein Blut für Öl!** (No to war in Iraq – no blood for oil!) was the largest in Switzerland since 1945.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Slovenia, roughly 3,000 people gathered in Ljubljana's central park of Congress Square, supported by the mayor Danica Simšič, and marched the streets in one of the largest demonstrations since independence in 1991.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Benelux countries had large demonstrations for their total population size.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Belgium organisers had expected around 30,000 people to attend a demonstration in Brussels, which is the home of the European Parliament.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] They were shocked by a turn out of approximately 100,000 people (WSWS and GLW estimate).
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The march took over 3 hours to cross the city.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Netherlands saw around 70,000 (*USA Today* estimate) to 75,000 people (WSWS estimate) protest in Amsterdam.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] This was the country's largest demonstration since the anti-nuclear campaigns of the 1980s.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Anti war website antiwar.com reports that 8,000-14,000 people were present at protests in Luxembourg, however they do not provide a citation for this figure.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Bosnia and Herzegovina saw around 100 protesters gather in Mostar.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] This protest spanned the sectarian divide with both Bosniaks and Croats attending.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There were also protests in Croatia where 10,000 people (WSWS estimate) took part in a protest in the capital city of Zagreb.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Croatia also saw protests in Osijek, Vukovar, Knin, Zadar, Šibenik, Split and Dubrovnik.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Cyprus saw a demonstration of between 500 (*USA Today* estimate) and more than 800 people (SW estimate) at the British army base in Dhekelia.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Enduring heavy rain protesters briefly blocked the base.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] They then marched to Pyla village where they watched other demonstrations occurring across the world on a giant screen.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The demonstration was mostly attended by Greek Cypriots but they were joined by some Turkish Cypriots.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In the Czech Republic, over 1,000 people joined a rally at Jan Palach Square in Prague.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Czech philosopher Erazim Kohak addressed the crowd, saying, "War is not a solution, war is a problem." Protesters listened to music and speeches before marching to the Czech government building, where they submitted petitions, then march continued to the US embassy.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In France, there were demonstrations in somewhere between twenty (*Observer* estimate) and eighty cities (WSWS estimate); the organisers estimated that over half a million marched in total.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The biggest demonstration took place in Paris, where around 100,000 (*USA Today* estimate) to 200,000 (WSWS estimate) people marched through the streets, ending in a rally at the Place de la Bastille.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] This location's role in the French Revolution was considered to give it a historical significance.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There was also a demonstration in Toulouse of around 10,000 people.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Germany, coaches brought people from over 300 German towns to Berlin to join a demonstration of 300,000 (police estimate) to 500,000 (organizers' estimate) people; the largest demonstration that had occurred in Berlin for several decades.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protesters, including members of Gerhard Schröder's government, filled the boulevard between the Brandenburg Gate and the Victory Column.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Athens, Greece, 150,000 people (WSWS estimate) demonstrated.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The protest was generally peaceful, but a small group clashed with police.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The police fired tear gas at the group some of whom threw rocks and petrol bombs.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Police reported that the trouble was down to a group of anarchists who had split off from the main demonstration.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Ireland, the Dublin march was only expected to draw 20,000 people, but the actual figure was given variously as 80,000 (police estimate), 90,000 (BBC estimate), 100,000 (*Guardian* estimate) or 150,000 (Socialist Worker (SW) estimate).
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The march went from Parnell Square, passing the Department of Foreign Affairs at St.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Stephen's Green, and on to the Dame Street for a rally where popular Irish folk singer Christy Moore, Kíla and Labour Party politician Michael D.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Higgins were among many speakers from the platform.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The march disrupted traffic for more than four hours.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protesters demanded that the Irish government stop allowing the United States military to use Ireland's Shannon Airport as a transatlantic stop-off point in bringing soldiers to the Middle East.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The biggest demonstration of the global day of protest took place in Italy in Rome.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Nearly 3,000 buses and thirty trains were specially chartered to bring people to the demonstration, which was organised under the slogan "Stop the war; no ifs or buts".
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The organisers were shocked at the size of the turn out and the unexpected number of people forced the demonstration to set off two hours early.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The size of the demonstration meant that the majority of demonstrators did not make it into the final rally and in total three million people (organisers' estimate, supported by the Guinness Book of World Records) were on the streets.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] This was listed in the 2004 Guinness Book of World Records as the largest anti-war rally in history.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] According to the *Green Left Weekly* (GLW), the demonstration contained people from across Italian society; "Catholic nuns and priests marched alongside young people with dreadlocks, nose rings and Palestinian scarves.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Christians, anarchists and communists mingled".
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Approximately 1,000 demonstrated (SW estimate) in Malta.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] After the demonstration an anti-war concert was held in the capital, Valletta.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Norway saw its biggest series of protests since 1917.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The biggest took place in its capital Oslo were more than 60,000 protesters (Police estimate and Socialist Worker estimate) joining a demonstration.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protests of around 15,000 took place in Bergen and Trondheim, and 10,000 in Stavanger.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Small protests also took place in at least 30 towns across the country.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] At the rally in Oslo the vice-chair of the Norwegian Confederation of Trade Unions (LO) spoke from the platform claiming that "Bush only cares about American oil interests".
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Denmark 20,000 to 30,000 protesters (WSWS estimate) took part in a march in the capital city, Copenhagen.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Sweden, 35,000 demonstrated in Stockholm. and about 25,000 in Gothenburg.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Helsinki, Finland, an estimated 15,000 people participated in one of the largest mass-protests in the republic's history.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There was a demonstration in Warsaw, Poland of 10,000 people (SW estimate).
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The demonstration through central Warsaw passed the US embassy.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Another protest, organized by the local Wrocław Anti-War Coalition (WKA), was held in the city of Wrocław in the market square by the town hall, with 400–500 people participating.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Lisbon, police estimated that around 35,000 people gathered to march through the city.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Three former Portuguese prime ministers were in attendance.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Russia, which had several demonstrations, the largest occurred in Moscow, with 200,000 people (WSWS estimate) in attendance.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Small demonstrations also took place in Serbia, where there was a demonstration of 200 people (WSWS estimate) in the capital city of Belgrade.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] It was estimated that 1,000 people marched in the capital of Slovakia, Bratislava.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Barcelona also had a large, with estimates of 350,000 (Delegación de Gobierno), 1,300,000 (Barcelona city hall and Police) or 1,500,000 (GLW) people joining a demonstration which moved from the Passeig de Gràcia to the Plaça de Tetuan.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The city of Oviedo had a population of 180,000 and a turnout of 100,000.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The main demonstration in Turkey took place in Istanbul, thousands (SW estimate) demonstrated.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The local authorities had banned the protest claiming to have worries about national security, however the protest organisers went ahead with the rally under the cover of calling a press conference.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There were also demonstrations in Adana, Ankara, İzmir, Zonguldak, İzmit, Antalya and Muğla.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There was also a demonstration in Ukraine of around 2,000 people (*USA Today* estimate) joined a "Rock against the war" rally in Kyiv's central square.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In the lead-up to 15 February, the Stop the War Coalition was organising the march from a small office donated by the National Association of Teachers in Further and Higher Education.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] They planned for the two marches to merge at Piccadilly Circus and then proceed to a rally at Hyde Park.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The negotiations for this plan faltered when the Labour government's Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport Tessa Jowell initially instructed the Royal Parks agency to deny permission for the rally in Hyde Park for safety reasons and to protect the grass.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Trafalgar Square was suggested by Jowell as the alternative venue, but the Mayor of London Ken Livingstone insisted it was of insufficient size.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The government's decision was reversed by 5 February.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Sections of the media supported this demonstration.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The *Daily Mirror* gave large coverage in the lead up to the march and provided thousands of placards on the day.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The demonstration also received sponsorship support from Greenpeace and Mecca-Cola.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] As the date for the march approached the BBC was predicting that around 500,000 people would attend, while StWC was hoping for numbers to top the symbolically significant million mark.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The British Stop the War Coalition (Stop) claimed the protest in London was the largest political demonstration in the city's history.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Police estimated attendance as well in excess of 750,000 people and the BBC estimated that around a million attended.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The weather, on the day of the protest was grey and cold, but reports noted that people remained "in high spirits" as London became gridlocked and protesters were stuck for hours at Gower Street and the Embankment, the two starting points for the march.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The police began the march earlier than intended on safety grounds because of the number of people who had arrived in central London.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Hundreds of coaches brought protesters from 250 towns and cities across the UK, with around 100 coaches coming from Wales alone.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Many commentators noted the diversity of those attending the march.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] All police leave in the capital was cancelled for the event, though Scotland Yard later said that it passed off almost without incident.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protesters who managed to reach Hyde Park in time heard various speakers, including Harold Pinter, George Galloway, Tony Benn and Bianca Jagger however many were not able to reach the rally as those travelling home by coach had to leave before completing the march route.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protesters at the back end of the march did not reach Hyde Park until hours after the speakers and performers had finished.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Charles Kennedy, then the leader of the Liberal Democrats, was a late addition to the list of speakers.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There was some media speculation that he only decided to speak after a lead article in *The Guardian* was critical of his absence from the planned speaker list.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Because of the size of the march, accurate estimates of the number of people in attendance are difficult.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] It is relatively uncontentious that the march was the largest ever political demonstration in the UK and the biggest taking to the streets since the Golden Jubilee weekend in 2002.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In an ICM poll for *The Guardian* (14 February 2003 – 16 February 2003), 6% of people claimed that someone from their household went on the march or had intended to.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Stop claims that this translates into 1.25 million households and thus supports the estimate of two million people, assuming that more than one person could come from each household.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] RadioVague in conjunction with the now defunct CableRadio broadcast speeches, music and interviews from the event to the internet throughout the day using a satellite uplink provided by Psand.net.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] A sole person demonstrated in opposition to the march outside the Iraqi section of the Jordanian Embassy on the day – Jacques More a writer from Croydon – with a placard saying that, although a last resort, war is necessary "[w]hen evil dictators rule and murder their own people".
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Ten years on writer Ian Sinclair assembled an oral history of the demonstration.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Journalist Ellie Mae O'Hagan, a UK Uncut activist, told Sinclair that despite its size "it did absolutely nothing".
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Other witnesses, such as Milan Rai, are of the opposite opinion: "We achieved a lot, and a hell of a lot more than we realise".
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Tariq Ali, one of the speakers in February 2003, said at the tenth anniversary: "I didn't quite tell them 'Blair is going to go to war regardless of today' but I knew that".
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] "It was a huge show of anger but that's about it.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] "One demonstration never overturned government policy overnight – or very rarely – and on something as strategic and massive as that", commented Seumas Milne in an interview with *The Quietus* online magazine in October 2012.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In addition to the demonstrations in England, the United Kingdom also saw protests in Scotland.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Anti-war activists planned a demonstration in Glasgow which ended at the Scottish Exhibition and Conference Centre (SECC) where the Labour Party was holding a conference for party members.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Labour Party requested that the SECC refuse permission for a stage and PA system outside the conference hall.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In response to this the then Scottish Socialist Party MSP Tommy Sheridan tabled a motion in the Scottish Parliament to allow the event to take place, condemning what he claimed were attempts to "stifle all opposition to warmonger Blair".
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Labour Party was unsuccessful in blocking the demonstrators' plans.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Tony Blair was due to give a speech at the same time as the protesters would have arrived outside the conference centre, but the speech was rescheduled to an earlier time to avoid this.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] On the day around 50,000 people according to the *Guardian* joined the march, which started at Glasgow Green.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] By the time the front of the march had travelled the 2 miles (3.2 km) to the SECC, Blair had delivered his speech and had left the area.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Northern Irish march was held in Belfast, where 10,000 (*Guardian* estimate) to 20,000 (SW estimate) protesters from across the sectarian divide joined the demonstration.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The march started at the Arts College at 14:30 and moved through that Royal Avenue towards Belfast City Hall.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Prominent politicians from Sinn Féin, the Social Democratic and Labour Party (SDLP) and the centrist Alliance Party joined the protest.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Sinn Féin president Gerry Adams spoke from the platform at the end rally saying "If President Bush and Mr Blair want war, it should be war against poverty and for equality." There was also a rally in Newry in County Down attending by hundreds of protesters (BBC estimate).
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Canada saw protests in 70 cities and towns (WSWS estimate).
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The biggest took place in Montreal where more than 100,000 people protested (SW and WSWS each estimated 150,000) despite windchill temperatures below −30 °C (−22 °F).
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] 80,000 people joined a demonstration in Toronto, 40,000 in Vancouver, 18,000 (by police estimates) in Edmonton, 8,000 in Victoria, 4,000 in Halifax and 6,000 in Ottawa.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There were protests in 70 cities in total.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] These demonstrations took place despite very cold weather, average temperatures were below −35 °C (−31 °F).
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Chicoutimi, 1,500 protested in windchill temperatures of −40 °C (−40 °F) wind-chill temperature in what was one of the coldest marches on that global day of protest.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protests took place all across the United States of America with CBS reporting that 150 U.S. cities had protests.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] According to the World Socialist Web Site, protests took place in 225 different communities.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The largest protests took place in the nation's largest cities including Chicago, Los Angeles, and New York City, but there were also smaller rallies in towns such as Gainesville, Georgia; Macomb, Illinois; and Juneau, Alaska, among scores of others.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Organisers of the New York City protest had hoped to march past the headquarters of the United Nations.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] However, a week before the march, police claimed that they would not be able to ensure order and District Court Judge Barbara Jones ruled against allowing the route.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Instead, protesters were only permitted to hold a stationary rally.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] On that day, over 300 buses and four special trains brought protesters in from across the country.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] BBC estimates that 100,000 protesters took part in a rally near the UN headquarters.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Among those taking part was the 9/11 Families For Peaceful Tomorrows, a group made up of some relatives of victims of the attacks on the World Trade Center.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Speakers included politicians, church leaders and entertainers, such as actress Susan Sarandon and South African Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] As people tried to reach the rally area they ended up constituting an unplanned march, stretching twenty blocks down First Avenue and overflowing onto Second and Third Avenue.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In total estimates range from 300,000 to 400,000 protesters (WSWS estimate).
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The protests were largely peaceful though a small group of protesters who were reported to have broken off from the main rally, caused damage to property in Union Square, and threw stones at police officers, which resulted in forty arrests.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There were numerous complaints that the New York City Police Department (NYPD) were too heavy-handed.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Many streets were blocked off and protesters reported feeling hemmed in and scared.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] By the end of the day, police reported that there had been roughly 275 arrests; organisers dispute this number, claiming that there were 348 arrests.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] However, NYPD spokesman Michael O'Looney denied the charges claiming that the tape was "filled with special effects" and that it did not prove the police had not been provoked.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] At a demonstration in Los Angeles, California, 50,000 (WSWS estimate) to 60,000 (GLW estimate) protesters (CNN said "thousands") marched down Hollywood Boulevard filling it for four blocks.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Amongst the protesters were the actors Martin Sheen and Mike Farrell and director Rob Reiner.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Martin Sheen, who at the time was playing a fictitious U.S. president in *The West Wing*, said that "None of us can stop this war ... there is only one guy that can do that and he lives in the White House".
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Other activists in California originally planned to hold a protest in San Francisco on the Saturday but they changed to the Sunday in order not to conflict with the city's Chinese New Year's parade.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The protest was held on Sunday 16 February.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The BBC estimated the crowd size to be 150,000 people, while protest organisers and police agreed that the crowd count was 200,000 people.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] However, a *San Francisco Chronicle* photographic investigation estimated that the number in attendance at the peak period was closer to 65,000 people, although it did not state how many people were in attendance for the duration of the demonstration.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There was some controversy over Rabbi Michael Lerner not being selected as a speaker for the rally at the end of the demonstration.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Lerner claimed that he was not picked to speak for reasons of antisemitism due to his support for the existence of the Israeli state.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Austin, Texas, 10,000 protestors marched down Congress Avenue from the state capitol building.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Colorado Springs, 4,000 protesters were dispersed with pepper spray, tear gas, stun guns and batons.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] 34 were arrested on failure to disperse and other charges and at least two protesters had to have hospital treatment.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Seattle, organisers aimed to have 20 to 30 thousand people join a march from Seattle Center following a giant blue planet, the emblem adopted by the march organisers.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] On the day 50,000 people (GLW estimate) turned out to protest under the dual slogan "Stop the war on Iraq; Stop the war on immigrants", more than on the Seattle protests against the WTO Ministerial Conference of 1999.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Demonstrations also took place in Philadelphia, where thousands (CNN estimate) joined a march to the Liberty Bell, and in Chicago, where 10,000 people demonstrated (GLW estimate).
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Florida a small number of protesters staged a naked protest on Palm Beach.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] They initially had some problems getting permission for the action, but on the Thursday before, a U.S.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] District court ruled that the planned nude protest was legal at the public beach.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Most of the attendees had come from the four-day Mid-Winter Naturist Festival that was taking place at the same time.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There was also a demonstration of 900 people (*USA Today* estimate) on the island of Puerto Rico.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The chief demonstration in Mexico took place in Mexico City where around 10,000 people (*USA Today* estimate) joined a demonstration which ended with a rally at a heavily guarded US embassy.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Among the demonstrators was Nobel Peace Prize laureate Rigoberta Menchú.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protests took place across South America including Uruguay, where their protest took place on 14 February.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] An estimated 70,000 people marched down Montevideo's Avenida 18.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Brazil, a protest led by President Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva was attended by 1,500 marchers (Police estimate).
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Buenos Aires, Argentina, an estimate of 50,000 protesters attended which included some veterans of the Falklands War of 1982.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Areas in Asia with large Muslim populations, in particular the countries of the West Asia, had the highest levels of opposition to the proposed Iraq war, however demonstrations in many of these countries were relatively small.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The reasons for this are complex, but one factor that is commonly cited is the suppression of protest movements by the conservative leaders of those countries.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Iraq, the country in which the war would take place, protesters marched down Palestine Street in Baghdad where several thousand Iraqis—many carrying Kalashnikov rifles—joined in the global protests.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Unlike the vast majority of protests across the world the protest in Baghdad was also in support of the Baathist regime; it was called by Saddam Hussein as "World Anger Day".
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protesters carried posters of Saddam and burned US flags.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] A large protest also took place on the streets of Damascus in Syria, which borders Iraq.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protesters chanted anti-U.S. and anti-Israeli slogans while marching to the "People's Assembly" in a demonstration of between 10,000 (GLW estimate) to 200,000 protesters (CBS estimate and *USA Today* estimate).
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Lebanon, 10,000 protesters (CBS, GLW estimate) took part in a demonstration in Beirut.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] However, the protest ended early when it rained heavily.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There were also demonstrations of 5,000 people (GLW estimate) in Amman, Jordan.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Israel there was a demonstration in Tel Aviv of approximately 2,000 (*USA Today* estimate) to 3,000 people (GLW and WSWS estimate).
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The demonstration contained both Arabs and Jews.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] It was organized by a wide range of organizations including the Communist Party of Israel, the National Democratic Assembly, the Arab Democratic Party, the Independent Media Center, the Alternative Information Center, Ta'ayush, the Gush Shalom movement, and the Organization for Democratic Action.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] However, it was boycotted by other left-wing groups, including Peace Now and Meretz.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The demonstration was coordinated with a similar demonstration which took place in Ramallah.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Small protests took place across Japan mostly being held outside US military bases.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The biggest demonstration of the day took place in Shibuya, where 5,000 (SW estimate) people marched.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] However, there was a demonstration of 25,000 in Tokyo on Friday, the day before as well as smaller demonstrations in Osaka and other cities.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Tokyo protests contained Japanese veterans of World War II and survivors of the 1945 atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Around 3,000 people (SW estimate) joined an illegal demonstration in the Malaysian city of Kuala Lumpur despite police warnings that any participants in a protest would face stern action.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The demonstration ended at the US embassy at Jalan Tun Razak.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Taiwan had a protest of more than 2,000 people (WSWS estimate) in the capital city of Taipei under the slogan of "No Blood for Oil".
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] India saw protests across the country including 10,000 (BBC estimate) in Calcutta.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Bangladesh 2,000 people joined a demonstration in Dhaka.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In South Korea, there was a demonstration of 2,000 people (WSWS estimate) which took place in the capital city Seoul.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The protest started with a rally at Marronnier Park after which there was a demonstration that ended in Jongmyo were the size of the protest increased in size to 3,000 people (WSWS estimate).
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Jongmyo was surrounded by riot police who almost out numbered the protesters.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protests also took place in the South Korean cities of Busan, Daegu, Daejeon, Gwangju and Wonju.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Beijing, China, three protests were held the following day, attended by about 450 people in total, including foreigners and domestic students.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Johannesburg, around 8,000-10,000 people joined in a colorful and peaceful protest.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] They toyi-toyied and marched, stopping at the U.S.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Consulate General where riot police formed a protective chain around the entrance.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Cape Town 5,000 (*USA Today* estimate) to 20,000 protesters (WSWS estimate) joined a demonstration march which started at 10 in the morning on Keizersgracht road and ended at the offices of the US consulate-general which was guarded by a ring of riot police, where there was a rally with speakers.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protests were organised by the Anti-War Coalition and the Stop the War campaign of the Congress of South African Trade Unions (Cosatu).
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protests of thousands of people also took place at Durban and Bloemfontein.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] A number of prominent ANC politicians attended marches.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] At the Cape Town rally the South African Minister, Pallo Jordan addressed the protesters saying; "We will stop the war.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] A protest of around 3,000 (SW estimate) in the Tunisian city of Sfax was attacked by police who beat the protesters with batons and truncheons, injuring at least 20.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protests in Fiji took place on the day before, on Friday morning, heralding the weekend of demonstrations.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Protesters handed floral Valentine's Day messages to the representatives of the US, British and Australian governments urging them to avoid the war.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Friday also saw protests in Melbourne, where around 150,000 people (BBC estimate) joined a demonstration.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] On the Saturday protests also took place in Australia's national capital (Canberra), with 20,000 protesters.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Sydney demonstration on Sunday 16 February included a feeder march of 10,000 trade unionists, with 200,000 (BBC estimate) to 250,000 (Sydney Morning Herald estimate) demonstrating in Sydney.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Across the six state capitals an estimated 600,000 demonstrated in cities around the country.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Beyond the capitals, many major cities and towns around Australia had protests.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] At protests in Australia in Bellingen, New South Wales around 2,500 people (SW estimate) joined a rally at the towns sports ground.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] As well as hearing from speakers, the demonstrators were entertained by a group of a cappella singers called 'The Bushbombs'.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The rally was about as large as the town's population.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The first actual demonstration of the day took place in New Zealand where 10,000 people demonstrated in Auckland and Wellington.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The Auckland march was bigger than expected, forcing police to shut off Queen Street.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] People were reported to be still starting the march as those at the front of the march reached a rally in Myers Park several kilometres away.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In Wellington the march had to carry on after the then planned end point as there were too many people to fit into the park.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Around 400 to 500 people marched in Hamilton.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] There were also protests in at least 18 other centres, including Dunedin, Thames, Opotiki, Whakatane, Whangarei, Timaru and Rotorua, and Picnic for Peace in Christchurch.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] A group of scientists at the US McMurdo Station held a rally on the ice at the edge of the Ross Sea.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] At the time, many commentators were hopeful that this global mobilization of unprecedented scale would stop the coming Iraq war.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] *The New York Times* writer Patrick Tyler claimed that they showed that there were "two superpowers on the planet – the United States, and worldwide public opinion".
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The unprecedented size of the demonstrations was widely taken to indicate that the majority of people across the world opposed the war.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] However, the potential effect of the protests was generally dismissed by pro-war politicians.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Her view was borne out as the day of protests, along with the protests that followed it, failed to stop the war.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] However, the protests and other public opposition were seen as a key factor in the decisions of the governments of many countries, such as Canada, to not send troops to Iraq, and of Turkey to deny coalition use of airbases in its territory.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] The protests have also been cited as a factor strengthening the hand of the "uncommitted six" members of the United Nations Security Council - Angola, Cameroon, Chile, Mexico, and Pakistan.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Though demonstrations against the Iraq war and subsequent occupation continued, none of the demonstrations through to 2011 matched the 15 February protest in terms of size.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] One suggested explanation for this is that people became disillusioned with marching as a political tactic because of the failure of these demonstrations to achieve their explicit aim.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] In 2006, three years after the protest day, in an article arguing for people to attend a further march, Mike Marqusee put forward two counter arguments to this.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Firstly, he claimed that it was too soon to judge the long-term significance of the demonstrations.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] As examples, he stated, "People who took part in the non-cooperation campaigns in India in the 20s and 30s had to wait a long time for independence," and "There were eight years of protest and more than 2 million dead before the Vietnam war came to an end".
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Secondly, he claimed that while the effect of marching may be uncertain, the effect of not marching would make it more likely that the occupation would continue.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] Despite failing in its explicit aim, the 15 February global day of anti-war protests had many effects that, according to some, were not directly intended.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] According to United Kingdom left-wing anti-war activist Salma Yaqoob, one of these was that they were a powerful antidote to the idea that the war was a "Clash of Civilizations", or a religious war, an idea she claimed was propagated both by Western leaders and reactionary forces in the Arab world.
[src:united-kingdom/15-february-2003-anti-war-protests] This is echoed in the words of former Hizb ut-Tahrir organiser Hadiya Masieh who said of the non-Muslims marching in London "How could we demonise people who obviously opposed aggression against Muslims?".
[src:united-kingdom/1871-england-versus-scotland-rugby-union-match] The **rugby union match played between Scotland and England** on 27 March 1871 was the world's first international rugby match.
[src:united-kingdom/1871-england-versus-scotland-rugby-union-match] It is also officially the first international football match in any football code.
[src:united-kingdom/1871-england-versus-scotland-rugby-union-match] The match was played at Raeburn Place, Edinburgh in front of 4,000 spectators.
[src:united-kingdom/1871-england-versus-scotland-rugby-union-match] Scotland won the match, scoring two tries and a goal to England's single try.
[src:united-kingdom/1871-england-versus-scotland-rugby-union-match] The match resulted from a challenge issued in the sporting weekly *Bell's Weekly* on 8 December 1870 and signed by the captains of five Scottish clubs, inviting any team "selected from the whole of England" to a 20-a-side game to be played under the rugby rules.
[src:united-kingdom/1871-england-versus-scotland-rugby-union-match] The game was played at Raeburn Place, Edinburgh, the home ground of Edinburgh Academicals, on 27 March 1871.
[src:united-kingdom/1871-england-versus-scotland-rugby-union-match] The English team wore all white, with a red rose on its shirts and the Scots, brown shirts with a thistle and white cricket flannels.
[src:united-kingdom/1871-england-versus-scotland-rugby-union-match] The team representing England was captained by Frederick Stokes of Blackheath; that representing Scotland was led by Francis Moncrieff. the umpires were Hely Hutchinson Almond, headmaster of Loretto School in Scotland, and A.
[src:united-kingdom/1871-england-versus-scotland-rugby-union-match] The matches for this season were decided on goals scored.
[src:united-kingdom/1871-england-versus-scotland-rugby-union-match] A goal was awarded for a successful conversion after a try, for a dropped goal or for a goal from mark.
[src:united-kingdom/1871-england-versus-scotland-rugby-union-match] If a game was drawn, any unconverted tries were tallied to give a winner.
[src:united-kingdom/1871-england-versus-scotland-rugby-union-match] If there was still no clear winner, the match was declared a draw.
[src:united-kingdom/1871-england-versus-scotland-rugby-union-match] The game, played over two halves, each of 50 minutes, was won by Scotland, who scored a goal with a successful conversion kick after grounding the ball over the goal line (permitting them to "try" to kick a goal).
[src:united-kingdom/1871-england-versus-scotland-rugby-union-match] Both sides achieved a further "try" each, but failed to convert them to goals, as the kicks were unsuccessful.
[src:united-kingdom/1871-england-versus-scotland-rugby-union-match] Angus Buchanan was the first man to score a try in international rugby.
[src:united-kingdom/1871-england-versus-scotland-rugby-union-match] In a return match at the Kennington Oval, London, in 1872, England were the winners.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] The **1908 Summer Olympics** (officially the **Games of the IV Olympiad** and also known as **London 1908**) were an international multi-sport event held in London, England, from 27 April to 31 October 1908.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] The 1908 Games were relocated to London after Italy withdrew from hosting on financial grounds.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] Archival research has established that the British Olympic Association was already privately exploring the possibility of London hosting the Games as early as 5 January 1906, three months before the eruption began.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] London was formally confirmed as host on 19 November 1906.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] Rome eventually hosted the Games in 1960.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] These were the fourth chronological modern Summer Olympics in keeping with the now-accepted four-year cycle as opposed to the alternate four-year cycle of the proposed Intercalated Games.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] The IOC president for these Games was Baron Pierre de Coubertin.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] Lasting a total of 187 days (six months and four days), these were the longest Games in modern Olympics history.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] There were four bids for the 1908 Summer Olympics.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] Rome was selected ahead of London, Berlin and Milan.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] The selection was made at the 6th IOC Session in London in 1904.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] Italian authorities were preparing to stage the games when Mount Vesuvius erupted on 7 April 1906, devastating the city of Naples.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] Funds were diverted to the reconstruction of Naples, so a new host country was required.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] During the Intercalated Games of Athens, still in April 1906, Coubertin approached Lord Desborough about alternatively hosting in London.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] Accepting the offer and with a mere 18 months in which to prepare, London was selected for the first time to hold the Games, which were held at White City alongside the Franco-British Exhibition, at the time the more noteworthy event.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] The White City Stadium, built in short time for the Games, held 68,000 people, with full crowds turning up to watch the events.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] The stadium track was three laps to the mile (536.448 metres per lap), as the current standard of 400 metres did not exist until 1962, with a pool (for swimming and diving events) and platforms (for wrestling and gymnastics) in the centre field.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] On the opening day, following the practice introduced at the Intercalated Games of 1906, teams paraded behind national flags.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] The 1908 Olympics also prompted establishment of standard rules for sports, and selection of judges from different countries rather than just the host.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] One reason was the 400 metre race, in which a US runner, John Carpenter, was accused by the British officials of interfering with a British runner.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] Part of the problem was the different definition of interference under British and international rules (the events were held under British rules by the decision of the Organising Committee).
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] The officials decided to disqualify Carpenter and ordered a second final race without him.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] British Halswelle was to face the other two finalists.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] These athletes, William Robbins and John Taylor, were both Americans and decided not to participate in the repeat of the final to protest against the judges' decision.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] Halswelle was thus the only medallist in the 400 metres.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] The most famous incident of the games came at the end of the marathon.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] Dorando Pietri, Italy, began his race at a rather slow pace, but in the second half of the course began a powerful surge moving him into second position by the 32 km (20 mi) mark, 4 minutes behind South African Charles Hefferon.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] When he knew that Hefferon was in crisis, Pietri further increased his pace, overtaking him at the 39 km (24 mi) mark.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] The effort took its toll and with only two kilometres to go, Pietri began to feel the effects of extreme fatigue and dehydration.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] When he entered the stadium, he took the wrong path and when umpires redirected him, he fell down for the first time.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] He got up with their help, in front of 75,000 spectators.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] He fell four more times, and each time the umpires helped him up.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] In the end, though totally exhausted, he managed to finish the race in first place.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] Of his total time of 2h 54min 46s, ten minutes were needed for that last 340 metres.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] The American team immediately lodged a complaint against the help Pietri received from the umpires.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] The complaint was accepted and Pietri was disqualified and removed from the final standings of the race.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] Since he had not been responsible for his disqualification, Queen Alexandra awarded him a gilded silver cup the next day.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] These Games were the first to include winter events, as had originally been proposed for the Games.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] There were four figure skating events, although held on 28 and 29 October, months after most of the other events.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] Oscar Swahn from Sweden, who won the gold medal for running deer shooting, became the oldest Olympic champion of all time, and set another age record by being 72 years and 279 days old during his triumph at the 1920 Summer Olympics in Antwerp, Belgium.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] One of the more unusual shooting events in 1908 was Olympic dueling.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] The discipline, which was an associate event (that is, not official), was performed by facing opponents wearing protective clothing and masks and firing wax bullets.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] American John Taylor was a member of the winning medley relay team, making him the first African-American athlete to win an Olympic gold medal.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] Times for the winning team were United States (3:29.4): William Hamilton, 200 metres (22.0); Nathaniel Cartmell, 200 metres (22.2); John Taylor, 400 metres (49.8); and Melvin Sheppard, 800 metres (1:55.4).
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] Less than five months after returning from the Olympic Games in London, Taylor died of typhoid fever on 2 December 1908 at the age of 26.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] The budget of the organising committee showed a cost of £15,000; over one-third was labelled "entertainment expense".
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] Donations were the major source of revenue; only 28% of income derived from ticket sales.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] Total receipts of £21,378 resulted in organisers claiming a profit.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] Construction of the White City Stadium, which cost the government about £60,000, was not counted.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] Twenty-two sports, representing 110 events in 25 sporting disciplines, were competed.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] A golf tournament had also been planned but it was cancelled a few days before it was scheduled to start.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] Swimming, diving, and water polo are considered three disciplines of the same sport, *aquatics*.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] At the time, tug-of-war was part of athletics and the two different football codes (association and rugby (union)) were listed together.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee now considers tug-of-war a separate sport as well as referring to association football as simply "football" and to rugby union as "rugby." In one of seven cycling events (cycling sprint) no medals were awarded.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] The sailing program was open for a total of five sailing classes, but actually only four sailing events were competed.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] The number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] Cycle polo, glima and pistol dueling were demonstration sports.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] Thirteen sports venues were used for the 1908 Summer Olympics.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] The first winter sports took place at Prince's Skating Club in Knightsbridge.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] White City Stadium served as a precursor to modern stadiums.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] The figure skating events were not held at the next Olympics in Stockholm, but returned for the 1920 Games in Antwerp, heralding the first Winter Olympics that took place in Chamonix in 1924.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] White City was the main venue for the 1934 British Empire Games (known as the Commonwealth Games since 1978) and, before its demolition in 1985, also served as a venue for the 1966 FIFA World Cup.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] The All England Lawn Tennis Club continues to host the Wimbledon championships and is the only venue of the 1908 Games that was used for the 2012 Summer Olympics.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] Bisley and Henley served as venues in the 1948 Games when the Olympics returned to London forty years later.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] The 1908 Games featured athletes representing 22 National Olympic Committees.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] Finland, Turkey and New Zealand (as part of the team from Australasia) made their first appearance at the Olympic Games.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] The fact that the United Kingdom competed as a single team was upsetting to some Irish competitors, who felt that Ireland should compete on its own, despite being part of the UK at the time.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] They relied on the precedent set by Grand Duchy of Finland, which while being a part of the Russian Empire, competed in London as a separate country.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] Fearing an Irish boycott, the authorities changed the name of the team to Great Britain/Ireland, and in two sports, field hockey and polo, Ireland participated as a separate country, winning silver medals in both, although their medals counted towards the UK's tally.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] Irish athletes in the United States were not affected by this controversy, and many Irish immigrants to the United States competed for the U.S.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] Olympic team as members of the Irish American Athletic Club.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] Members of the Irish American Athletic Club won ten of the U.S.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] Olympic team's total 23 gold medals, or as many as the nations of France, Germany and Italy combined.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] Britain had more than a quarter of competitors in their team, with 676, compared to 112 on the American team which placed second in the medal standings.
[src:united-kingdom/1908-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1908 Games.
[src:united-kingdom/1928-equal-franchise-act] The **Representation of the People (Equal Franchise) Act 1928** (18 & 19 Geo.
[src:united-kingdom/1928-equal-franchise-act] 12) was an act of the Parliament of the United Kingdom.
[src:united-kingdom/1928-equal-franchise-act] This act expanded on the Representation of the People Act 1918 (7 & 8 Geo.
[src:united-kingdom/1928-equal-franchise-act] 64) which had given some women the vote in Parliamentary elections for the first time after World War I.
[src:united-kingdom/1928-equal-franchise-act] It is sometimes referred to as the **Fifth Reform Act**.
[src:united-kingdom/1928-equal-franchise-act] The act widened suffrage by giving women electoral equality with men.
[src:united-kingdom/1928-equal-franchise-act] It gave the vote to all women over 21 years old, regardless of property ownership.
[src:united-kingdom/1928-equal-franchise-act] Prior to this act only women over 30 who met minimum property qualifications could vote.
[src:united-kingdom/1928-equal-franchise-act] The act was passed by the Conservative Party without much opposition from other parties.
[src:united-kingdom/1928-equal-franchise-act] The bill became law on 2 July 1928, having been introduced in March.
[src:united-kingdom/1928-equal-franchise-act] The leader of the National Union of Women's Suffrage Societies who had campaigned for the vote, Millicent Fawcett, was still alive and attended the parliament session to see the vote take place.
[src:united-kingdom/1928-equal-franchise-act] She wrote in her diary the same night "It is almost exactly 61 years ago since I heard John Stuart Mill introduce his suffrage amendment to the Reform Bill on 20 May 1867.
[src:united-kingdom/1928-equal-franchise-act] On 5 August 1928, Millicent Fawcett obtained a letter from the prime minister Stanley Baldwin.
[src:united-kingdom/1928-equal-franchise-act] He points out that even though there were obstacles in passing the bill, he always believed it would be ratified in "the simple and complete form it ultimately assumed".
[src:united-kingdom/1928-equal-franchise-act] He finishes the letter by expressing a hope that equal vote would be beneficial for the country and it would serve for the greater good in the United Kingdom.
[src:united-kingdom/1928-equal-franchise-act] Section 8(1) of the act provided that the act may be cited as the "Representation of the People (Equal Franchise) Act, 1928" and may be cited as a Representation of the People Act.
[src:united-kingdom/1928-equal-franchise-act] Section 8(4) of the act provided that the act would extend to Northern Ireland so far as it relates to matters with respect to which the Parliament of Northern Ireland have no power to make laws.
[src:united-kingdom/1928-equal-franchise-act] The act added five million more women to the electoral roll and made women a majority, 52.7%, of the electorate in the 1929 general election, which was termed the "Flapper Election".
[src:united-kingdom/1928-equal-franchise-act] The whole act was repealed by section 80(7) of, and the thirteenth schedule to, the Representation of the People Act 1948 (11 & 12 Geo.
[src:united-kingdom/1928-equal-franchise-act] 65), which came into force on 30 July 1948.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] The **1948 Summer Olympics**, officially the **Games of the XIV Olympiad** and officially branded as **London 1948**, were an international multi-sport event held from 29 July to 14 August 1948 in London, United Kingdom.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Following a twelve-year hiatus caused by the outbreak of World War II, these were the first Summer Olympics held since the 1936 Games in Berlin.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] The 1940 Olympic Games had been scheduled for Tokyo and then for Helsinki, while the 1944 Olympic Games had been provisionally planned for London.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] This was the second time London hosted the Olympic Games, having previously hosted them in 1908, making it the second city to host the Summer Olympics twice (after Paris).
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] The Olympics would return again to London 64 years later in 2012, making London the first city to host the games three times, and the only such city until Paris, who hosted their third games in 2024, and Los Angeles, who will host theirs in 2028.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] The 1948 Olympic Games were also the first of two summer Games held under the IOC presidency of Sigfrid Edström.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] The 1948 Summer Olympics were the only Summer Olympics to be held in the 1940s, as the 1940 and 1944 Summer Olympics were cancelled due to World War II.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] It was also the first Summer Olympics that took place during the Cold War.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] The 1948 Olympics came to be known as the "Austerity Games" due to the difficult economic climate and the rationing imposed in the aftermath of World War II.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] A record 59 nations were represented by 4,104 athletes, 3,714 men, and 390 women in 19 sport disciplines.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Germany and Japan were not invited to participate in the games; the Soviet Union was invited but chose not to send any athletes, sending observers instead to prepare for the 1952 Olympics.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Israel requested to participate (symbolically represented by Raya Bronstein and Frieda Berson-Lichtblau) but was denied as the International Olympic Committee did not yet recognize the country, while the Olympic mandate of Palestine expired.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] This in turn shifted the view of the Arab countries who had intended to boycott the event and now decided to take part.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] One of the star performers at the 1948 Games was Dutch sprinter Fanny Blankers-Koen.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Dubbed the "Flying Housewife", the thirty-year-old mother of two won four gold medals in athletics.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] In the decathlon, Bob Mathias of the United States became the youngest male ever to win an Olympic track and field gold medal at the age of seventeen.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] The most individual medals were won by Veikko Huhtanen of Finland, who took three golds, a silver and a bronze in men's gymnastics.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] The United States topped the medal table.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] In June 1939, the International Olympic Committee (IOC) awarded the 1944 Olympic Summer Games to London, ahead of Rome, Detroit, Budapest, Lausanne, Helsinki, Montreal and Athens.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] World War II stopped the plans and the Games were cancelled so London again stood as a candidate for 1948.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Great Britain almost handed the 1948 games to the United States due to post-war financial and rationing problems, but King George VI said that hosting the Olympics would help to restore Britain from World War II.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] The official report of the London Olympics shows that London was not pressed to run the Games against its will.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] and saw the president of the International Olympic Committee to discuss the question of London being chosen for this great event.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] As a result, an investigating committee was set up by the British Olympic Council to work out in some detail the possibility of holding the Games.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] should be invited to apply for the allocation of the Games in 1948.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] In June 1946 the IOC, through a postal vote, gave the summer Games to London and the winter competition to St Moritz.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] London was selected ahead of Baltimore, Minneapolis, Lausanne, Los Angeles, and Philadelphia.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] London, which had previously hosted the 1908 Summer Olympics, became the second city to host the Olympics twice; Paris hosted the event in 1900 and 1924.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] London later became the first city to host the Olympics for a third time when the city hosted the 2012 Summer Olympics.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Lord Burghley, a gold medal winner at the 1928 Olympics, member of the International Olympic Committee (IOC), and president of the Amateur Athletics Association was named Chairman of the Organising and Executive Committees.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] The other members of the committees were: Colonel Evan Hunter, General Secretary of the British Olympic Association, and Chief de mission for Great Britain; Lord Aberdare, the other British member of the IOC; Sir Noel Curtis-Bennett; Alderman H.E.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Emrys Lloyd, who became the committee's legal advisor; C.B.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Cowley of the London Press and Advertising; R.B.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Studdert, managing director of the Army & Navy Stores; A.E.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Porritt, a member of the IOC for New Zealand who resided in London; S.F.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Rous, Secretary of The Football Association; and Jack Beresford.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Olympic pictograms were introduced for the first time.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] There were twenty of them—one for each Olympic sport and three separate pictograms for the arts competition, the opening ceremony and the closing ceremony.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] They were called "Olympic symbols" and intended for use on tickets.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] The background of each pictogram resembled an escutcheon.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Olympic pictograms appeared again 16 years later, and were used at all subsequent Summer Olympics.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] At the time of the Games, food, petrol and building were still subject to the rationing imposed during the war in Britain; because of this the 1948 Olympics came to be known as the "Austerity Games".
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Athletes were given the same increased rations as dockers and miners, 5,467 calories a day instead of the normal 2,600.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Building an Olympic Village was deemed too expensive, and athletes were housed in existing accommodation.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Male competitors stayed at RAF camps in Uxbridge and West Drayton, and an Army camp in Richmond Park; female competitors in London colleges.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Lord Burghley unfurled the Olympic Flag at the Richmond Park camp at an opening ceremony in July as Minister of Works, Charles Key, declared the camp open.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] These were the first games to be held following the death of Pierre de Coubertin, founder of the International Olympic Committee, in 1937.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] They were also the last to include an arts competition, which took place at the Victoria and Albert Museum.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Nicknamed "relay of peace" due to crossing through several countries in Europe to represent their union after the Second World War, the torch relay for these games took place from 17 to 29 July 1948, with a distance of 3,160 kilometres (1,960 mi) and 1,416 torchbearers.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] There were three types of torches: the standard one made of aluminium and powered by solid fuel, a special one powered by butane gas (used aboard HMS *Whitesand Bay*) and a third one used in the Wembley stadium, made of stainless steel and powered by a magnesium candle.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] The journey began with the lighting of the flame in Olympia.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Due to the civil war taking place in Greece, the Greek part of the relay went directly to Corfu, where HMS *Whitesand Bay* picked the flame to transport it to Bari.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] From there, the flame crossed Italy, Switzerland, France, Luxembourg and Belgium.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] After a boat trip from Calais to Dover (aboard of HMS *Bicester*), the flame traveled to several towns in Southeast England until the arrival at Wembley for the Opening ceremony.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Army bands began playing at 2 pm for the 85,000 spectators in Empire Stadium at Wembley Park.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] The international and national organisers arrived at 2.35 pm and King George VI and Queen Elizabeth, with Queen Mary and other members of the Royal Family, at 2.45 pm.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Fifteen minutes later the competitors entered the stadium in a procession that took 50 minutes.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] The last team was that of the United Kingdom.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] A visionary dream has today become a glorious reality.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] At the end of the worldwide struggle in 1945, many institutions and associations were found to have withered and only the strongest had survived.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] How, many wondered, had the great Olympic Movement prospered?
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] At 4 pm, the time shown on the clock tower on the London Games symbol, the King declared the Games open, 2,500 pigeons were set free and the Olympic Flag raised to its 35 ft (11 m) flagpole at the end of the stadium.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] The Royal Horse Artillery sounded a 21-gun salute to welcome the last runner in the Torch Relay: John Mark, a British track and field sprinter and student at the University of Cambridge with impressive Olympian good looks.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Mark ran a lap of the track – created with cinders from the domestic coal fires of Leicester – and climbed the steps to the Olympic cauldron.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] After saluting the crowd, he turned and lit the flame.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] After more speeches, Donald Finlay of the British team (given his RAF rank of Wing Commander) took the Olympic Oath on behalf of all competitors.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] The National Anthem was sung and the massed athletes turned and marched out of the stadium, led by Greece, tailed by Britain.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Thus were launched the Olympic Games of London, under the most happy auspices.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony and over 60 hours of Games coverage was broadcast live on BBC television, which was then officially available only in the London area.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] However, the BBC's transmissions could be received much further away in the right conditions, and some of the Games were watched by at least one viewer in the Channel Islands.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] The BBC's official report on the coverage estimated that an average of half a million viewers watched each of their Olympic broadcasts.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] The BBC paid £1,000 for the broadcasting rights.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Of the live television coverage, only a small section of the opening ceremony broadcast still exists in the archives.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] However, various filmed reports shot for the BBC's *Television Newsreel* program do also still exist.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] The 1948 Summer Olympics featured 136 medal events, covering 23 disciplines in 17 different sports and in arts.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] In the list below, the number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] These Games also included Lacrosse and Swedish (Ling) gymnastics as demonstration sports.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Empire Stadium was the venue for 33 athletics events at the Games; 24 for men and nine for women.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Of these, four were making their Olympic debut – the men's 10 km walk, and the women's 200 metres, long jump and shot put.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] A total of 754 athletes from 53 countries participated in athletics.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Fanny Blankers-Koen of the Netherlands, a 30-year-old mother of two children nicknamed "The Flying Housewife", won four gold medals, in the 100 metres, 200 metres, 80 metre hurdles, and 4 x 100 metre relay.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] As world record holder in the long jump and high jump Blankers-Koen may have been able to win further medals but, at this time, female athletes were limited to three individual events.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Duncan White won the first medal of any kind for Sri Lanka (then Ceylon) when he finished second in the 400 metre hurdles.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Arthur Wint became the first Jamaican to win an Olympic gold medal, in the men's 400 metres; he also won silver in the men's 800 metres.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Audrey Patterson became the first African-American woman to win a medal, winning bronze in a track and field event.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] A few days later Alice Coachman became the first woman of colour in the world and the first African-American woman to win a gold medal in track and field in the history of the modern Olympics with a jump of 1.68 m (5' 61⁄4").
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] She also was the only American woman to win an athletics gold medal during the 1948 Olympics.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] The marathon saw a dramatic finish with the first man to enter the stadium, Etienne Gailly of Belgium, exhausted and nearly unable to run.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] While he was struggling, Argentinian athlete Delfo Cabrera and Tom Richards of Great Britain passed him, with Cabrera winning the gold medal and Richards obtaining the silver.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Gailly managed to recover enough to cross the line for the bronze.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] The decathlon was won by 17-year-old Bob Mathias of the United States.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Categories: sports-related architecture, literature, music, painting, and sculpture.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] These Olympics were the last time art competitions were considered Olympic events.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Basketball made its second appearance as a medal sport, appearing as an indoor competition for the first time after poor weather disrupted the matches at the 1936 Berlin Games.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] The event, for men only, was contested by 23 nations split into four pools for the preliminary round; the top two in each pool advanced to the quarterfinals with the other teams entering playoffs for the minor placings.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] The United States and France reached the final which was won by the Americans 65–21 to claim the gold medal.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] This was the second of the United States' seven consecutive gold medals in Olympic men's and women's basketball.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Brazil defeated Mexico 52–47 to claim bronze.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Eight different classifications were contested ranging from flyweight, for boxers weighing less than 51 kg, to heavyweight, for boxers over 80 kg.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] South Africa, Argentina and Hungary each won two gold medals.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Nine events were contested, eight for men and one for women.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] This marked the first time that a women's canoeing event had been contested in the Olympics.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Sweden won four gold medals (two by Gert Fredriksson) and Czechoslovakia three.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Six events were contested – two road bicycle racing events and four track cycling events.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] No women's cycling events were contested.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] France won three gold medals and Italy two, while Great Britain captured five medals overall, but none were gold.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Four diving events were contested, two for men, and two for women.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] The events are labelled as 3 metre springboard and 10 metre platform by the International Olympic Committee but appeared on the 1948 Official Report as *springboard diving* and *highboard diving*, respectively.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] All four gold medals, and 10 out of 12 awarded in total, were won by the United States.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Victoria Manalo Draves, who won both gold medals in the women's events, and Sammy Lee, who took a gold and a bronze in the men's events, became the first Asian Americans to win gold medals at an Olympic Games.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Six gold medals were awarded in equestrian, individual and team dressage, individual and team eventing and individual and team show jumping.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Harry Llewellyn and Foxhunter, who would claim a gold medal in Helsinki, won bronze in the team jumping event.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Seven events were contested, six for men and one for women.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Ilona Elek, who had won the women's foil competition in Berlin, was one of only two competitors to successfully defend an Olympic title in London.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Elek's sister, Margit, placed sixth in the same event.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Edoardo Mangiarotti won three medals, two silver and a bronze, having previously won a gold medal in the 1936 Games.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Throughout his career the Italian won 13 Olympic fencing medals and 27 world championship medals, both of which remain records.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Thirteen nations participated in the field hockey competition.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] The tournament was ultimately won by India, who defeated Great Britain to claim the country's first gold medal as an independent nation under captain Kishan Lal and Vice-Captain Kunwar Digvijay Singh.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Eighteen teams entered the football competition at these Olympics.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Due to the rise of the professional game during the 12 years since the Berlin Olympics the number of talented amateurs for teams to select from was reduced.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] The gold medal was won by Sweden, who defeated Yugoslavia 3–1 in the final.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Denmark defeated hosts Great Britain, managed by Matt Busby of Manchester United, 5–3 to win the bronze medal.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] In the tournament's 18 matches a total of 102 goals were scored; an average 5.66 goals per match.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] The joint top scorers with seven goals each were Gunnar Nordahl of Sweden and Denmark's John Hansen.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Nordahl and Swedish teammates Gunnar Gren and Nils Liedholm went on to play for A.C.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Milan and together were nicknamed Gre-No-Li.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] This was the first international football tournament ever to be broadcast on television, with the two semi-finals, the bronze medal match and the final all being shown live in full by the BBC.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Nine events were contested, eight for men, and one for women.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] In the men's pommel horse, a tie was declared between three competitors, all Finns, and no medals other than gold were awarded in this event.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Finland won six gold medals overall, and Switzerland three.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Lacrosse was an exhibition sport at these Olympics.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] An English team composed of players from various universities played a U.S. team represented by Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute at the Empire Stadium.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Only one modern pentathlon event was contested, the five component sports– riding, fencing, shooting, swimming, and running- being held over six days.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Scoring was by point-for-place system across the five phases with the winner being the athlete with the lowest combined ranking.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] The sport's international federation, the Union Internationale de Pentathlon Moderne was founded during the Games, on 3 August 1948.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Sweden won two medals in the event; William Grut won the gold, with a final points total of 16, and Gösta Gärdin took bronze.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] American George Moore won the silver medal.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Seven rowing events were contested, all open to men only.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Great Britain and the United States each claimed two gold medals.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] The events were held on the River Thames at Henley, over the same course as the Henley Royal Regatta.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] The sailing events at the Games took place in Torquay, in the southwest of Great Britain.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Five events were contested, with the United States winning four total medals.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] One of host nation Great Britain's three gold medals at the Games came in the Swallow class from Stewart Morris and David Bond.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] In the Firefly class Danish sailor Paul Elvstrøm won gold the despite the Danish Olympic Committee having misgivings about sending him to compete as the 18-year-old could speak no English.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] This was the first of four consecutive Olympics with a gold medal for Elvstrøm.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Four events were contested, all open to both men and women, although all medals were won by men.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] In the 50 metre rifle, prone position, only two points separated the top three competitors.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Károly Takács had been a member of the Hungary's world champion pistol shooting team in 1938 when a grenade shattered his right hand – his pistol hand.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Takács taught himself to shoot with his left hand and, 10 years after his injury, he won an Olympic gold medal in the rapid-fire pistol event.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Eleven events were contested, six for men and five for women.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] The United States won eight gold medals, including all six men's events, and 15 medals in total.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Eighteen nations fielded a team in these games, which were ultimately won by Italy, who were undefeated throughout.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] The tournament was conducted in a mult-tier bracket, with the best four teams from the group stages participating in a final round-robin bracket.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Silver was claimed by Hungary, and bronze by the Netherlands.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Six events were contested, all for men only.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] These games marked the addition of the bantamweight class to the Olympic programme, the first change to the programme since 1920.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] The United States won four gold medals, and eight overall; the remaining two gold medals were claimed by Egypt.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Sixteen wrestling events were held, eight Greco-Roman and eight freestyle.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Both categories were dominated by two nations.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Turkey was the most successful nation with six gold medals followed by Sweden receiving 5 gold medals.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] These two teams claimed 24 total medals, in other words half of the total medals given.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] London was the first Olympics to have a political defection.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Marie Provazníková, the 57-year-old Czechoslovak President of the International Gymnastics Federation, refused to return home, citing "lack of freedom" after the Czechoslovak coup in February led to the country's inclusion in the Soviet Bloc.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] For the 1948 Olympics, the Technicolor Corporation devised a bipack colour filming process – dubbed "Technichrome" – whereby hundreds of hours of film documented the events in colour, without having to use expensive and heavy Technicolor cameras.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Slightly over 2,000 journalists attended the 1948 Games.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] A cinder track was laid inside Empire Stadium and all other venues were adapted.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] For the first time at the Olympics swimming events were held undercover, at the 8000 capacity Empire Pool.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] As the pool was longer than the standard Olympic length of 50 metres a platform was constructed across the pool which both shortened it and housed officials.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] In 2010 one of the last remaining venues from the Games, the Herne Hill Velodrome where cycling events were staged, was saved when a new 15-year lease was agreed meaning that repairs could take place.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Campaigners and users of the track had feared that it would be forced to close as it was in desperate need of refurbishment.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Thirteen made their first official appearance: British Guiana (now Guyana), Burma (now Myanmar), Ceylon (now Sri Lanka), Iraq, Jamaica, Korea, Lebanon, Pakistan, Puerto Rico, Singapore, Syria, Trinidad and Tobago, and Venezuela.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] It was the first time that Australia, New Zealand, Philippines, India and Pakistan competed as fully independent nations at the Olympic Games.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Germany and Japan, under Allied military occupations, were not allowed to send athletes to the games.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Due to continuing labour shortages, German prisoners of war were used for the construction of the facilities for the games, in particular Olympic Way.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Italy, although originally an Axis power, had defected to the Allies in 1943 following Benito Mussolini being deposed, and was allowed to send athletes.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] The Soviet Union was invited but chose not to send any athletes, sending observers instead to prepare for the 1952 Olympics.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] The nations that returned to the games were Cuba, Iran (The last participation of a Persian athlete was in Paris 1900), Ireland, Panama and Spain.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Other nations, besides Germany and Japan, that participated in the previous games in Berlin 1936 but were absent in London 1948 were Bolivia, Bulgaria, Costa Rica, Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] In the case of the Baltic nations, they had been occupied and annexed by the Soviet Union, only returning to the games many decades later.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Bulgaria, Romania and Mandatory Palestine accepted invitations for the Games but withdrew a few days before it began.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Puerto Rico, an unincorporated territory and commonwealth of the United States, made its Olympic debut as an independent team.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] Bermuda, Jamaica, Trinidad and Tobago, Singapore and British Guyana were part of the British Empire.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1948 Summer Games, ranked by number of gold medals won.
[src:united-kingdom/1948-summer-olympics] The host nation was 12th, with 27 medals, including four golds.
[src:united-kingdom/gb] The domain was introduced with RFC 920 in October 1984 that set out the creation of ccTLD generally using country codes derived from the corresponding two-letter code in the ISO 3166-1 list.
[src:united-kingdom/gb] However, the .uk domain had been created separately a few months before the compilation of this list.
[src:united-kingdom/gb] Consequently, .gb was never widely used.
[src:united-kingdom/gb] It is no longer possible to register under this domain.
[src:united-kingdom/gb] .gb was used for a number of years, mainly by British government organisations and commercial e-mail services using X.400-based e-mail infrastructure.
[src:united-kingdom/gb] This simplified translating between DNS domains and X.400 addresses, which used "GB" as a country code.
[src:united-kingdom/gb] With the demise of X.400 e-mail and IANA's general aim of one TLD per country, use of .gb declined; the domain remains in existence, but it is not currently open to new domain registrations.
[src:united-kingdom/gb] As of 2025, there are at least three subdomains resolving through DNS (although none serve a web page or use): `hermes.dra.hmg.gb`, `delos.dra.hmg.gb`, and `dfhnet.dra.hmg.gb`.
[src:united-kingdom/gb] They were originally owned by the Defence Research Agency, which became the Defence Evaluation and Research Agency in 1995 and was split into QinetiQ and the Defence Science and Technology Laboratory in 2001; the websites became defunct some time thereafter.
[src:united-kingdom/gb] As of November 2022, Central Digital and Data Office's intention was to inform ICANN early in 2023 that the UK wishes to retire the .gb ccTLD.
[src:united-kingdom/uk] In October 1984, RFC 920 set out the creation of ccTLDs using country codes derived from the corresponding two-letter code in the ISO 3166-1 list.
[src:united-kingdom/uk] However, the UK academic network Name Registration Scheme, JANET NRS, had defined "UK" as the top-level domain a few months before the compilation of the ISO-derived list.
[src:united-kingdom/uk] Consequently, .uk was chosen and registered on 24 July 1985. .gb was reserved but never widely used and it is no longer possible to register domains under that ccTLD.
[src:united-kingdom/uk] As with other ccTLDs in the early days it was originally delegated by Jon Postel to a "trusted person" to manage.
[src:united-kingdom/uk] Andrew McDowell at UCL was assigned .uk, the first country code delegation.
[src:united-kingdom/uk] In time, he passed it to Willie Black at the UK Education and Research Networking Association (UKERNA).
[src:united-kingdom/uk] Originally, domain requests were emailed, manually screened by and then forwarded to the UK Naming Committee before being processed by UKERNA.
[src:united-kingdom/uk] Membership of this committee was restricted to a group of high-end ISPs who were part of a formal peering arrangement.
[src:united-kingdom/uk] The Naming Committee was organised as a mailing list to which all proposed names were circulated.
[src:united-kingdom/uk] The members would consider the proposals under a ruleset that insisted that all domain names should be very close if not identical to a registered business name of the registrant.
[src:united-kingdom/uk] Members of the Naming Committee could object to any name, and if at least a small number of objections were received, the name was refused.
[src:united-kingdom/uk] By the mid-1990s the growth of the Internet, and particularly the advent of the World Wide Web was pushing requests for domain name registrations up to levels that were not manageable by a group of part-time volunteers.
[src:united-kingdom/uk] Oliver Smith of Demon Internet forced the issue by providing the committee with a series of automated tools, called the "automaton", which formalised and automated the naming process end to end.
[src:united-kingdom/uk] This allowed many more registrations to be processed far more reliably and rapidly, and inspired individuals such as Ivan Pope to explore more entrepreneurial approaches to registration.
[src:united-kingdom/uk] Various plans were put forward for the possible management of the domain, mostly Internet service providers seeking to stake a claim, each of which were naturally unacceptable to the rest of the committee.
[src:united-kingdom/uk] In response to this Black, as the .uk Name, stepped up with a bold proposal for a not-for-profit commercial entity to deal with the .uk domain properly.
[src:united-kingdom/uk] Commercial interests initially balked at this, but with widespread support Nominet UK was formed in 1996 to be the .uk Network Information Centre, a role which it continues to this day.
[src:united-kingdom/uk] The general form of the rules (i.e. which domains can be registered and whether to allow second level domains) was set by the Naming Committee.
[src:united-kingdom/uk] Nominet has not made major changes to the rules, although it has introduced a new second level domain .me.uk for individuals.
[src:united-kingdom/uk] Until 10 June 2014 it was not possible to register a domain name directly under .uk (such as *internet.uk*); it was only possible as a third-level domain (such as *internet.co.uk*).
[src:united-kingdom/uk] Currently, management of the .uk domain name is delegated by IANA to Nominet UK.
[src:united-kingdom/uk] It is possible to directly register a domain name with Nominet UK at £80+VAT as of 2021, but it is faster and cheaper to do it via a Nominet-accredited domain registrar costing in the region of £10+VAT in 2021.
[src:united-kingdom/uk] If a domain was registered before 23:59 UTC on 28 October 2013 the user had the rights to the equivalent .uk domain (providing there was no other corresponding .co.uk, .org.uk, me.uk, .ltd.uk, .plc.uk or .net.uk registered).
[src:united-kingdom/uk] For example, if "your-company.co.uk" was held since 2 October 2013, the registrant of 'your-company.co.uk' had the reserved right of registering "your-company.uk", up until 06:00 BST on 25 June 2019.
[src:united-kingdom/uk] 123-reg and NamesCo both created such domains for their customers for free but then began demanding payment in September 2019.
[src:united-kingdom/uk] .co.uk, .ltd.uk, .me.uk, .net.uk, .nic.uk, .org.uk, .plc.uk and .sch.uk are managed by Nominet UK and except for .nic.uk are available for registration by the public (though they all carry various degrees of restrictions).
[src:united-kingdom/uk] Other second-level domains are managed by various government agencies, and generally more strongly controlled.
[src:united-kingdom/uk] Allocations are on a strict first-come, first-served basis to qualified applicants.
[src:united-kingdom/uk] There are no territorial restrictions: applicants need not have any connection to the UK other than those outlined below for .ltd.uk and other restricted domains.
[src:united-kingdom/uk] .co.uk is by far the most used of the domains, followed by .org.uk then .me.uk. .plc.uk and .ltd.uk are only rarely used.
[src:united-kingdom/uk] The number of new registrations for each of the different .uk domains on a month by month basis can be seen on the Nominet UK website.
[src:united-kingdom/uk] The intended restriction of .co.uk to companies is purely nominal; in practice it is open to any and all applicants.
[src:united-kingdom/uk] Likewise, whilst .org.uk is for organisations, there are no restrictions on registering domains.
[src:united-kingdom/uk] While .me.uk originally had no restrictions on registrants it has since been tightened up to require registrants to be natural persons (i.e. not companies, etc.).
[src:united-kingdom/uk] However, registrants in .ltd.uk must be, and remain, private limited companies incorporated under the UK Companies Acts.
[src:united-kingdom/uk] In addition, names can only be registered if they correspond (in accordance with the algorithm in the rules of registration) with the exact company name, as recorded at the companies registry at Companies House.
[src:united-kingdom/uk] The same conditions apply for public limited companies which wish to use a .plc.uk domain name.
[src:united-kingdom/uk] Neither of these domains is widely used.
[src:united-kingdom/uk] .net.uk is more open, but the Nominet regulations still mean that a registrant must be an ISP, or a similar body, and that the domain is not used for providing services to end-users. .nic.uk, however, is limited solely to domains operated by Nominet.
[src:united-kingdom/uk] .ac.uk domains are intended for the use of higher education institutions and further education colleges, and are also used by some academic support bodies such as the Universities and Colleges Admissions Service public research establishments, and learned societies such as the Royal Society.
[src:united-kingdom/uk] Primary and secondary education uses .sch.uk.
[src:united-kingdom/uk] Unusually, .sch.uk domains are allocated at the fourth level, with the third level being taken up by the name of the local authority (LA, previously LEA or local education authority) e.g. schoolname.leaname.sch.uk.
[src:united-kingdom/uk] For example, the Little Ilford School in Newham has the domain name littleilford.newham.sch.uk and the West Exe School in Exeter, Devon has the domain name westexe.devon.sch.uk.
[src:united-kingdom/uk] Previously applications were made in the normal way, but after Nominet came to an arrangement with the education authorities, one domain per school was issued automatically.
[src:united-kingdom/uk] Those that had already used another domain were still given one and were able to redirect it to their main domain.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The **United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland**, commonly known as the **United Kingdom** (**UK**) or **Britain**, is a country in northwestern Europe, off the coast of the continental mainland.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] It comprises England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland, with a population of over 69 million in 2024.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The UK includes the island of Great Britain, the north-eastern part of the island of Ireland, and most of the smaller islands within the British Isles, covering 94,354 square miles (244,376 km2).
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] It shares a land border with the Republic of Ireland and is surrounded by the Atlantic Ocean, the North Sea, the English Channel, the Celtic Sea and the Irish Sea, while maintaining sovereignty over the Crown Dependencies and the British Overseas Territories.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The capital and largest city of England and the UK is London; Edinburgh, Cardiff and Belfast are the national capitals of Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland, respectively.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The British Isles have been continuously inhabited since the Neolithic.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] In AD 43 the Roman conquest of Britain began.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The Roman departure between 383 and 410 was followed by Anglo-Saxon settlement beginning around 450.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Over the 17th century the role of the British monarchy was reduced, particularly as a result of the English Civil War.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] In 1707 the Kingdom of England and the Kingdom of Scotland united under the Treaty of Union to create the Kingdom of Great Britain.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The Acts of Union 1800 incorporated the Kingdom of Ireland to create the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland in 1801.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Most of Ireland seceded from the UK in 1922 as the Irish Free State, and the Royal and Parliamentary Titles Act 1927 created the present United Kingdom.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The UK became the first industrialised country and was the world's foremost power for the majority of the 19th and early 20th centuries, particularly during the *Pax Britannica* between 1815 and 1914.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] At its height in the 1920s, the empire encompassed around a quarter of the world's landmass and population, and was the largest in history.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] However, its involvement in the First World War and in the Second World War damaged Britain's economic power, and a global wave of decolonisation led to the independence of most British colonies.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The UK is a constitutional monarchy and parliamentary democracy with three distinct jurisdictions: England and Wales, Scotland, and Northern Ireland.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland have their own governments and parliaments which control various devolved matters.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] A developed country with an advanced economy, the UK ranks amongst the largest economies by nominal GDP and is one of the world's largest exporters and importers.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] As a nuclear state with one of the highest defence budgets, the UK maintains one of the strongest militaries in Europe.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] British culture is globally influential, notably in the Anglosphere and the Commonwealth; its soft power influence is observable in the legal and political systems of many former colonies, and in its exports of language, literature, theatre, cinema, music, art and sport.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] A great power, the UK is part of numerous international organisations.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The Acts of Union 1707 declared that the Kingdom of England and the Kingdom of Scotland were "United into One Kingdom by the Name of Great Britain".
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The term "United Kingdom" has occasionally been used for the former Kingdom of Great Britain, although its official name from 1707 to 1800 was simply "Great Britain".
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The Acts of Union 1800 formed the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Following the partition of Ireland and the independence of the Irish Free State in 1922, which left Northern Ireland as the only part of the island of Ireland within the United Kingdom, the name was changed in 1927 to the "United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland".
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Although the United Kingdom is a sovereign country, England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland are widely referred to as countries.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The UK Prime Minister's website has used the phrase "countries within a country" to describe it.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Some statistical summaries, such as those for the twelve NUTS 1 regions, refer to Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland as "regions".
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Northern Ireland is also referred to as a "province".
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] With regard to Northern Ireland, the descriptive name used "can be controversial, with the choice often revealing one's political preferences".
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The term "Great Britain" conventionally refers to the island of Great Britain, or politically to England, Scotland and Wales in combination.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] It is sometimes used as a loose synonym for the United Kingdom as a whole.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The word *England* is occasionally used incorrectly to refer to the United Kingdom as a whole, a mistake principally made by people from outside the UK.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The term "Britain" is used as a synonym for Great Britain, but also sometimes for the United Kingdom.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The BBC historically preferred to use "Britain" as shorthand only for Great Britain, though the present style guide does not take a position except that "Great Britain" excludes Northern Ireland.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The adjective "British" is commonly used to refer to matters relating to the United Kingdom and is used in law to refer to United Kingdom citizenship and nationality.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] People of the United Kingdom use several different terms to describe their national identity and may identify themselves as being British, English, Scottish, Welsh, Northern Irish or Irish; or as having a combination of different national identities.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Settlement by Cro-Magnons of what was to become the United Kingdom occurred in waves beginning by about 30,000 years ago.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The island has been continuously inhabited since the last retreat of ice around 11,500 years ago.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] By the end of the region's prehistoric period, the population is thought to have belonged largely to a culture termed Insular Celtic, comprising Brittonic Britain and Gaelic Ireland.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Most of the region settled by the Anglo-Saxons became unified as the Kingdom of England in the 10th century.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Gaelic speakers in north-west Britain (with connections to the north-east of Ireland and traditionally supposed to have migrated from there in the 5th century) united with the Picts to create the Kingdom of Scotland in the 9th century.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] In 1066 the Normans invaded England from northern France.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] After conquering England they seized large parts of Wales, conquered much of Ireland and were invited to settle in Scotland, bringing to each country feudalism on the Northern French model and Norman-French culture.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The Anglo-Norman ruling class greatly influenced, but eventually assimilated with, the local cultures.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Subsequent medieval English kings completed the conquest of Wales and tried unsuccessfully to annex Scotland.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Asserting its independence in the 1320 Declaration of Arbroath, Scotland maintained its independence thereafter, albeit in near-constant conflict with England.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] In 1215 Magna Carta was the first document to state that no government was above the law and that citizens have rights protecting them.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The English monarchs, through inheritance of substantial territories in France and claims to the French crown, were also heavily involved in conflicts in France, most notably the Hundred Years' War, while the Kings of Scots were in an alliance with the French during this period.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Early modern Britain saw religious conflict resulting from the Reformation and the introduction of Protestant state churches in each country.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The English Reformation ushered in political, constitutional, social and cultural change in the 16th century and established the Church of England.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] It defined a national identity for England and slowly, but profoundly, changed people's religious beliefs.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Wales was fully incorporated into the Kingdom of England, and Ireland was constituted as a kingdom in personal union with the English crown.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] During the Plantation of Ulster in the 17th century, the lands of the Catholic Gaelic nobility were confiscated by the Crown and granted to Protestant settlers from England and Scotland.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The Union of the Crowns occurred in 1603 when James VI of Scotland inherited the thrones of England and Ireland, subsequently moving his court from Edinburgh to London.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Although unified under a single monarch, the three realms remained entirely separate political entities, preserving their respective parliaments, judicial systems, and established churches.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The British constitution would develop on the basis of constitutional monarchy and the parliamentary system.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] With the founding of the Royal Society in 1660, science was greatly encouraged.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] During this period, particularly in England, the development of naval power and the interest in voyages of discovery led to the acquisition and settlement of overseas colonies, particularly in North America and the Caribbean.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Though previous attempts at uniting the two kingdoms within Great Britain in 1606, 1667 and 1689 had proved unsuccessful, the attempt initiated in 1705 led to the Treaty of Union of 1706 being agreed and ratified by both parliaments.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] On 1 May 1707 the Kingdom of Great Britain was formed, the result of the Acts of Union 1707 between the Kingdom of England and Kingdom of Scotland.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] In the 18th century cabinet government developed under Robert Walpole, who is considered the *de facto* first prime minister from 1721 to 1742.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] A series of Jacobite uprisings sought to remove the Protestant House of Hanover from the throne and restore the Catholic House of Stuart.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] In 1746, the Jacobites were defeated at the Battle of Culloden, after which the Scottish Highlanders were forcibly assimilated into Scotland by revoking the feudal independence of clan chiefs.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The British colonies in North America that broke away in the American War of Independence became the United States.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] British imperial ambition turned towards Asia, particularly to India.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] British merchants played a leading part in the Atlantic slave trade, mainly between 1662 and 1807 when British or British-colonial slave ships transported nearly 3.3 million slaves from Africa.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The slaves were taken to work on plantations, principally in the Caribbean but also in North America.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] In 1800, the parliaments of Great Britain and Ireland each passed an Act of Union, uniting the two kingdoms and creating the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland on 1 January 1801.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] After the defeat of France at the end of the French Revolutionary Wars and Napoleonic Wars (1792–1815), the United Kingdom emerged as the principal naval and imperial power (with London the largest city in the world from about 1830).
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Unchallenged at sea, British dominance was later described as the *Pax Britannica* ("British Peace"), a period of relative peace amongst the great powers (1815–1914) during which the British Empire became the global hegemon and adopted the role of global policeman.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] From 1853 to 1856 Britain took part in the Crimean War, allied with the Ottoman Empire against Tsarist Russia.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Following the Indian Rebellion of 1857 the British government led by Lord Palmerston assumed direct rule over India.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Alongside the formal control it exerted over its own colonies, British dominance of much of world trade meant that it effectively controlled the economies of regions such as East Asia and Latin America.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Throughout the Victorian era (1837–1901) political attitudes favoured free trade and *laissez-faire* policies.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Beginning with the Great Reform Act in 1832, Parliament gradually widened the voting franchise, with the 1884 Reform Act championed by William Gladstone granting suffrage to a majority of males for the first time.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The British population increased at a dramatic rate, accompanied by rapid urbanisation, causing significant social and economic stresses.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] During this time, Canada, Australia and New Zealand were granted self-governing dominion status.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] At the turn of the 20th century, Britain's industrial dominance became challenged by the German Empire and the United States.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The Edwardian era (1901–1910) saw social reform and home rule for Ireland become important domestic issues, while the Labour Party emerged from an alliance of trade unions and small socialist groups in 1900, and suffragettes campaigned for women's right to vote.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Britain was one of the principal Allies that defeated the Central Powers in the First World War (1914–1918).
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Alongside their French, Russian and (after 1917) American counterparts, British armed forces were engaged across much of the British Empire and in several regions of Europe, particularly on the Western Front.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The high fatalities of trench warfare caused the loss of much of a generation of men, with lasting social effects in the nation and a great disruption in the social order.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Britain had suffered 2.5 million casualties and finished the war with a huge national debt.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The consequences of the war persuaded the government to expand the right to vote in national and local elections to all adult men and most adult women with the Representation of the People Act 1918.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] After the war Britain became a permanent member of the Executive Council of the League of Nations and received a mandate over a number of former German and Ottoman colonies.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Under the leadership of David Lloyd George, the British Empire reached its greatest extent, covering a fifth of the world's land surface and a quarter of its population.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] By the mid-1920s most of the British population could listen to BBC radio programmes.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Experimental television broadcasts began in 1929 and the first scheduled BBC Television Service commenced in 1936.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The rise of Irish nationalism, and disputes within Ireland over the terms of Irish Home Rule, led eventually to the partition of the island in 1921.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] A period of conflict in what is now Northern Ireland occurred from June 1920 until June 1922.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The Irish Free State became independent, initially with Dominion status in 1922, and unambiguously independent in 1931.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Northern Ireland remained part of the United Kingdom.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The 1928 Equal Franchise Act gave women electoral equality with men in national elections.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Strikes in the mid-1920s culminated in the General Strike of 1926.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] A coalition government was formed in 1931.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Nonetheless, Britain was described as "a very wealthy country, formidable in arms, ruthless in pursuit of its interests and sitting at the heart of a global production system." After Nazi Germany's invasion of Poland in 1939, Britain entered the Second World War.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Despite the defeat of its European allies in the first year, Britain and its empire continued the war against Germany.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] In 1940 the Royal Air Force successfully defended British airspace by repelling the German *Luftwaffe* in the Battle of Britain.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Urban areas suffered heavy bombing during the Blitz.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The Grand Alliance of Britain, the United States and the Soviet Union formed in 1941, leading the Allies against the Axis powers.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] There were eventual hard-fought victories in the Battle of the Atlantic, the North Africa campaign and the Italian campaign.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] British forces played important roles in the Normandy landings of 1944 and the liberation of Europe.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The British Army led the Burma campaign against Japan, and the British Pacific Fleet fought Japan at sea.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] British scientists contributed to the American Manhattan Project, whose task was to build a nuclear weapon.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The United Kingdom was one of the Big Three powers (with the United States and the Soviet Union) who met to plan the post-war world; it drafted the Declaration by United Nations with the United States and became one of the five permanent members of the United Nations Security Council.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] It worked closely with the United States to establish the International Monetary Fund, the World Bank and NATO.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The war left the UK severely weakened and financially dependent on the American Marshall Plan, but it was spared the total war that devastated eastern Europe.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] In the immediate post-war years the Labour government under Clement Attlee initiated a radical programme of reforms, which significantly affected British society in the following decades.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Major industries and public utilities were nationalised, a welfare state was established, and a comprehensive, publicly funded healthcare system, the National Health Service, was created.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The rise of nationalism in the colonies coincided with Britain's much-diminished economic position after its involvement in the First World War and in the Second World War, so that a policy of decolonisation was unavoidable.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Independence was granted to India and Pakistan in 1947.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Over the next three decades, most colonies of the British Empire gained their independence, and many became members of the Commonwealth of Nations.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The UK was the third country to develop a nuclear weapons arsenal, with its first atomic bomb test, Operation Hurricane, in 1952, although the post-war limitations of Britain's international role were illustrated by the Suez Crisis of 1956.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] As a result of a shortage of workers in the 1950s, the government encouraged immigration from Commonwealth countries.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] In the following decades the UK became a more multiracial and multicultural society.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Despite rising living standards in the late 1950s and 1960s, the United Kingdom's economic performance was less successful than many of its main competitors such as France, West Germany and Japan.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The United Kingdom was the first democratic nation to lower its voting age to 18 in 1969.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] In the decades-long process of European integration the UK was a founding member of the Western European Union, established with the London and Paris Conferences in 1954.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] In 1960 the UK was one of the seven founding members of the European Free Trade Association (EFTA), but in 1973 it left to join the European Communities (EC).
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] In a 1975 referendum 67 per cent voted to stay in it.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] When the EC became the European Union (EU) in 1993, the UK was one of the 12 founding member states.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] From the late 1960s, Northern Ireland experienced communal and paramilitary violence, sometimes affecting other parts of the UK, known as the Troubles.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] It is usually considered to have ended with the 1998 Belfast "Good Friday" Agreement.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] In 1982, Argentina invaded the British territories of South Georgia and the Falkland Islands, leading to the 10-week Falklands War in which Argentine forces were defeated.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The inhabitants of the islands strongly favour British sovereignty, expressed in a 2013 referendum.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] From 1984 the British economy was helped by the inflow of substantial North Sea oil revenues.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Another British Overseas Territory, Gibraltar, is a key military base; a referendum in 2002 on shared sovereignty with Spain was rejected.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Around the end of the 20th century, major changes were made to the governance of the UK with the establishment of devolved administrations for Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The statutory incorporation followed acceptance of the European Convention on Human Rights.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The UK remained a great power with global diplomatic and military influence and a leading role in the United Nations and NATO.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The United Kingdom broadly supported the United States' approach to the "war on terror" in the early 21st century.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] British troops fought in the war in Afghanistan, but controversy surrounded Britain's military deployment in Iraq, which saw the largest protest in British history in opposition to the government led by Tony Blair.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The Great Recession (2007–2010) severely affected the British economy, and was followed by a period of weak growth and stagnation.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The Cameron–Clegg coalition government of 2010 introduced austerity measures intended to tackle the substantial public deficits.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] A referendum on Scottish independence in 2014 resulted in the Scottish electorate voting by 55.3 to 44.7 per cent to remain part of the United Kingdom.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] In 2016, 51.9 per cent of voters in the UK voted to leave the European Union (EU).
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] On 1 May 2021 the EU–UK Trade and Cooperation Agreement, a free trade agreement between the UK and the EU, came into force.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The COVID-19 pandemic had a severe impact on the British economy, caused major disruptions to education and had far-reaching impacts on society and politics in 2020 and 2021.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The United Kingdom was the first country in the world to use an approved COVID-19 vaccine.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Developing a vaccine in the UK allowed the rollout to be amongst the fastest in the world.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The total area of the United Kingdom is approximately 94,354 square miles (244,376 km2), with a land area of 93,723 square miles (242,741 km2).
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] It occupies the major part of the British Isles and includes the island of Great Britain, the north-eastern one-sixth of the island of Ireland and some smaller surrounding islands, meaning it comprises England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Geographically, the United Kingdom lies between the North Atlantic Ocean and the North Sea with the southeast coast coming within 22 miles (35 km) of the coast of northern France, from which it is separated by the English Channel.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The Isle of Man lies roughly midway between Great Britain and the island of Ireland in the Irish Sea, while the Channel Islands lie just off the northern French coast.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The Royal Greenwich Observatory in London was chosen as the defining point of the Prime Meridian at the International Meridian Conference in 1884.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The UK lies between latitudes 49° and 61° N, and longitudes 9° W and 2° E.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Northern Ireland shares a 310-mile (499 km) land boundary with the Republic of Ireland and has a 404-mile (650 km) coastline.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The length of coastline of Great Britain plus its principal islands is about 19,491 miles (31,368 km) long, with the coastline of the main island Great Britain being 11,073 miles (17,820 km) of that, though measurements can vary greatly due to the coastline paradox.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] It is connected to continental Europe by the Channel Tunnel, which at 31 miles (50 km) (24 miles (38 km) underwater) is the longest underwater tunnel in the world.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The UK contains four terrestrial ecoregions: Celtic broadleaf forests, English Lowlands beech forests, North Atlantic moist mixed forests, and Caledonian conifer forests.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The area of woodland in the UK was estimated to be 3.25 million hectares in 2023, which represents 13 per cent of its land area.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Most of the United Kingdom has a temperate climate, with generally cool temperatures and plentiful rainfall all year round.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The temperature varies with the seasons seldom dropping below 0 °C (32 °F) or rising above 30 °C (86 °F).
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Some parts, away from the coast, of upland England, Wales, Northern Ireland and most of Scotland, experience a subpolar oceanic climate.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Higher elevations in Scotland experience a continental subarctic climate and the mountains experience a tundra climate.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The prevailing wind is from the southwest and bears frequent spells of mild and wet weather from the Atlantic Ocean, although the eastern parts are mostly sheltered from this wind.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Since the majority of the rain falls over the western regions, the eastern parts are the driest.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Atlantic currents, warmed by the Gulf Stream, bring mild winters, especially in the west where winters are wet and even more so over high ground.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Summers are warmest in the southeast of England and coolest in the north.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Heavy snowfall can occur in winter and early spring on high ground, and occasionally settles to great depth away from the hills.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The average total annual sunshine in the United Kingdom was 1,339.7 hours between 1971 and 2000.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The hours of sunshine vary from 1,200 to about 1,580 hours per year.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Climate change has serious impacts on the country.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] A third of food price rise in 2023 was attributed to it.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] In 2024 the United Kingdom ranked 5th out of 180 countries in the Environmental Performance Index.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] A law has been passed that UK greenhouse gas emissions will be net zero by 2050.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] England accounts for 53 per cent of the UK, covering 50,350 square miles (130,395 km2).
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Most of the country consists of lowland terrain, with upland and mountainous terrain northwest of the Tees–Exe line which roughly divides the UK into lowland and upland areas.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Lowland areas include Cornwall, the New Forest, the South Downs and the Norfolk Broads.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Upland areas include the Lake District, the Pennines, the Yorkshire Dales, Exmoor and Dartmoor.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The main rivers and estuaries are the Thames, Severn, and the Humber.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] England's highest mountain is Scafell Pike, at 978 metres (3,209 ft) in the Lake District; its largest island is the Isle of Wight.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Scotland accounts for 32 per cent of the UK, covering 30,410 square miles (78,772 km2).
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] This includes nearly 800 islands, notably the Hebrides, Orkney Islands and Shetland Islands.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Scotland is the most mountainous constituent country of the UK.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The Highlands to the north and west are the more rugged region containing the majority of Scotland's mountainous land, including the Cairngorms, Loch Lomond and The Trossachs and Ben Nevis which at 1,345 metres (4,413 ft) is the highest point in the British Isles.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Wales accounts for less than 9 per cent of the UK, covering 8,020 square miles (20,779 km2).
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] It is mostly mountainous, though South Wales is less mountainous than North and Mid Wales.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The highest mountains in Wales are in Snowdonia and include Snowdon (Welsh: *Yr Wyddfa*) which, at 1,085 metres (3,560 ft), is the highest peak in Wales.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Wales has over 1,680 miles (2,704 kilometres) of coastline including the Pembrokeshire Coast.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Several islands lie off the Welsh mainland, the largest of which is Anglesey (*Ynys Môn*).
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] Northern Ireland, separated from Great Britain by the Irish Sea and North Channel, has an area of 5,470 square miles (14,160 km2) and is mostly hilly.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] It includes Lough Neagh which, at 150 square miles (388 km2), is the largest lake in the British Isles by area, Lough Erne, which has over 150 islands, and the Giant's Causeway, which is listed by UNESCO as a World Heritage Site.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p01] The highest peak in Northern Ireland is Slieve Donard in the Mourne Mountains at 852 metres (2,795 ft).
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The United Kingdom is a constitutional monarchy and a parliamentary democracy operating under the Westminster system, otherwise known as a "democratic parliamentary monarchy".
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] It is a centralised, unitary state wherein the Parliament of the United Kingdom is sovereign.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Parliament is made up of the elected House of Commons, the appointed House of Lords and the Crown (as personified by the monarch).
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The main business of Parliament takes place in the two houses, but royal assent is required for a bill to become an act of Parliament (that is, statute law).
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] As a result of parliamentary sovereignty, the British constitution is uncodified, consisting mostly of disparate written sources, including parliamentary statutes, judge-made case law and international treaties, together with constitutional conventions.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Nevertheless, the Supreme Court recognises a number of principles underlying the British constitution, such as parliamentary sovereignty, the rule of law, democracy and upholding international law.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] King Charles III is the monarch and head of state of the United Kingdom and 14 other independent sovereign states, referred to as "Commonwealth realms".
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The monarch is formally vested with all executive authority as the personal embodiment of the Crown and is "fundamental to the law and working of government in the UK".
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The disposition of such powers however, including those belonging to the royal prerogative, is generally exercised only on the advice of ministers of the Crown responsible to Parliament and thence to the electorate.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Nevertheless, in the performance of official duties the monarch has "the right to be consulted, the right to encourage, and the right to warn".
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In addition the monarch has a number of reserve powers at his disposal to uphold responsible government and prevent constitutional crises.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The prime minister is the head of government in the United Kingdom.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Nearly all prime ministers have served concurrently as First Lord of the Treasury and all prime ministers have continuously served as First Lord of the Treasury since 1905, Minister for the Civil Service since 1968, and Minister for the Union since 2019.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] While appointed by the monarch, in modern times the prime minister is, by convention, an MP, the leader of the political party with the most seats in the House of Commons, and holds office by virtue of their ability to command the confidence of the House of Commons.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The prime minister as at 2025 is Sir Keir Starmer, the leader of the Labour Party.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Although not part of the United Kingdom, the three Crown Dependencies of Jersey, Guernsey and the Isle of Man, as well as the 14 British Overseas Territories, are subject to the sovereignty of the British Crown.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Democratic backsliding was found by the 2026 V-Dem Democracy Report for the United Kingdom.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] For general elections (elections to the House of Commons), the United Kingdom is divided into 650 constituencies, each of which is represented by one member of Parliament (MP) elected by the first-past-the-post system.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] MPs hold office for up to five years and must then stand for re-election if they wish to continue to be an MP.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The Conservative Party, colloquially known as the Tory Party or the Tories, and the Labour Party have been the dominant political parties in the country since the 1920s, leading to the UK being described as a two-party system.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] However, since the 1920s other political parties have won seats in the House of Commons, although never more than the Conservatives or Labour.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The 2020s marked the erosion of the two-party system and the growth of a multi-party system.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The geographical division of the United Kingdom into counties or shires began in England and Scotland in the early Middle Ages, and was completed throughout Great Britain and Ireland by the early modern period.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Until the 19th century there was little change to those arrangements, but there has since been a constant evolution of role and function.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Local government in England is complex, with the distribution of functions varying according to local arrangements.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The upper-tier subdivisions of England are the nine regions, used primarily for statistical purposes.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] One of the regions, Greater London, has had a directly elected assembly and mayor since 2000 following popular support for the proposal in a 1998 referendum.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Local government in Scotland is divided into 32 council areas with a wide variation in size and population.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The cities of Glasgow, Edinburgh, Aberdeen and Dundee are separate council areas, as is the Highland Council, which includes a third of Scotland's area but only just over 200,000 people.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Local councils are made up of elected councillors, of whom there are 1,223.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Local government in Wales consists of 22 unitary authorities, each led by a leader and cabinet elected by the council itself.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] These include the cities of Cardiff, Swansea and Newport, which are unitary authorities in their own right.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Elections are held every four years under the first-past-the-post system.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Local government in Northern Ireland since 1973 has been organised into 26 district councils, each elected by single transferable vote.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Their powers are limited to services such as waste collection, dog control, and maintaining parks and cemeteries.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In 2008 the executive agreed on proposals to create 11 new councils to replace the existing system.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] These powers vary and have been moved to the Scottish Government, the Welsh Government, the Northern Ireland Executive and (in England) to strategic authorities: the Greater London Authority, combined authorities, and combined county authorities.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Amongst the devolved parliaments across the United Kingdom, the Scottish Parliament has the most extensive responsibilities for devolved powers, and has been described as "one of the most powerful devolved parliaments in the world".
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The United Kingdom has an uncodified constitution and constitutional matters are not amongst the powers that have been devolved.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Under the doctrine of parliamentary sovereignty, the UK Parliament could, in theory, therefore, abolish the Scottish Parliament, Senedd or Northern Ireland Assembly.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Though in the Scotland Act 2016 and the Wales Act 2017 it states that the Scottish Government and the Welsh Government "are a permanent part of the United Kingdom's constitutional arrangements".
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In practice it would be politically difficult for the UK Parliament to abolish devolution to the Scottish Parliament and the Senedd because these institutions were created by referendums.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The political constraints placed upon the UK Parliament's power to interfere with devolution in Northern Ireland are greater still, because devolution in Northern Ireland rests upon an international agreement with the Government of Ireland.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The UK Parliament restricts the three devolved parliaments' legislative powers in economic policy matters through an act passed in 2020.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Unlike Scotland, Northern Ireland and Wales, England does not have a separate devolved government or national parliament, rather a process of devolution of powers from the central government to local authorities has taken place, first in 1998.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The Greater London Authority was set up following a referendum in 1998.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Colloquially known as City Hall, it is the devolved regional government body for Greater London.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] It consists of two political branches: a directly elected Mayor of London and the London Assembly, which serves as a check and balance on the Mayor.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] A combined authority is a type of local government institution introduced in England outside Greater London by the Local Democracy, Economic Development and Construction Act 2009.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] CAs allow a group of local authorities to pool appropriate responsibility and receive certain devolved functions from central government in order to deliver transport and economic policy more effectively over a wider area.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] A combined county authority is a similar type of local-government institution introduced in England outside Greater London by the Levelling-up and Regeneration Act 2023, but may only be formed by upper-tier authorities: county councils and unitary authorities.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Since 1999 Scotland has had a devolved national government and parliament with wide-ranging powers over any matter that has not been specifically reserved to the UK Parliament.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Scotland has the most devolved powers of any of the three devolved parliaments in the United Kingdom, with full legislative control over education, law and order, the economy, healthcare, elections, Crown Estate Scotland, the planning system and housing.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Their power over economic issues is significantly constrained by an act of the UK Parliament passed in 2020.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The Scottish Government is a Scottish National Party (SNP) minority government, led by the first minister, currently John Swinney, the leader of the SNP.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In 2014 the Scottish independence referendum was held, with 55.3 per cent voting against independence from the United Kingdom and 44.7 per cent voting in favour, resulting in Scotland staying within the United Kingdom.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The Scottish Parliament is separate from the Scottish Government.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] It is made up of 129 elected members of the Scottish Parliament (MSPs).
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] It is the law-making body of Scotland, and thus it scrutinises the work of the incumbent Scottish Government and considers any piece of proposed legislation through parliamentary debates, committees and parliamentary questions.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Since 1999 Wales has had a devolved national government and legislature, known as the Senedd.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Elections to the Senedd used the additional member system until 2026 when the voting system was changed to closed list proportional representation.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The number of elected members also increased from 60 to 96, representing 16 six-member constituencies.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The Senedd has more limited powers than those devolved to Scotland.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] It can legislate on any matter not specifically reserved to the UK Parliament by Acts of Senedd Cymru.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The Welsh Government is currently a Plaid Cymru minority government led by the first minister, Rhun ap Iorwerth.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The devolved form of government in Northern Ireland is based on the 1998 Good Friday Agreement, which brought to an end a 30-year period of unionist-nationalist communal conflict known as the Troubles.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The Agreement was confirmed by referendum and implemented later that year.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] It established power sharing arrangements for a devolved government and legislature, referred to as the Northern Ireland Executive and the Northern Ireland Assembly respectively.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Elections to the Assembly use the single transferable vote system.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The Executive and Assembly have powers similar to those devolved to Scotland.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The Executive is led by a diarchy representing unionist and nationalist members of the Assembly.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The first minister and deputy first minister of Northern Ireland are the joint heads of government of Northern Ireland.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Local government in Northern Ireland since 2015 has been divided between 11 councils with limited responsibilities.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The United Kingdom is a permanent member of the United Nations Security Council and a member of NATO, AUKUS, the Commonwealth of Nations, the G7, the G20, the OECD, the WTO, the Council of Europe and the OSCE.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] It maintains the British Council, an organisation specialising in international cultural and educational opportunities in over 100 countries.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The UK remains a great power with considerable political, cultural, economic and military influence.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The UK is also closely linked with the Republic of Ireland; the two countries share a Common Travel Area and co-operate through the British-Irish Intergovernmental Conference and the British-Irish Council.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Britain's global presence and influence is further amplified through its trading relations, foreign investments, official development assistance and military engagements.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The British Armed Forces consist of three professional service branches: the Royal Navy and Royal Marines (forming the Naval Service), the British Army and the Royal Air Force.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The armed forces of the United Kingdom are managed by the Ministry of Defence and controlled by the Defence Council, chaired by the Secretary of State for Defence.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The Commander-in-Chief is the British monarch, to whom members of the forces swear an oath of allegiance.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The armed forces are charged with protecting the United Kingdom and its overseas territories, promoting the UK's global security interests and supporting international peacekeeping efforts.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] They are active and regular participants in NATO (including the Allied Rapid Reaction Corps), the Five Power Defence Arrangements, RIMPAC and other worldwide coalition operations.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Overseas garrisons and facilities are maintained in Ascension Island, Bahrain, Belize, Brunei, Canada, Cyprus, Diego Garcia, the Falkland Islands, Germany, Gibraltar, Kenya, Oman, Qatar and Singapore.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] According to the Stockholm International Peace Research Institute and the International Institute for Strategic Studies, the UK had the world's sixth- or fifth-highest military expenditures in 2025.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Total defence spending in 2024 was estimated at 2.3 per cent of gross domestic product.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Following the end of the Cold War, defence policy has a stated assumption that "the most demanding operations" will be undertaken as part of a coalition.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The United Kingdom does not have a single legal system as the 1706 Treaty of Union provided for the continuation of Scotland's separate legal system.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The UK has three distinct systems of law: English law, Northern Ireland law and Scots law.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] A new Supreme Court of the United Kingdom came into being in October 2009 to replace the Appellate Committee of the House of Lords.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The Judicial Committee of the Privy Council, including the same members as the Supreme Court, is the highest court of appeal for several independent Commonwealth countries, the British Overseas Territories and the Crown Dependencies.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Both English law, which applies in England and Wales, and Northern Ireland law are based on common law (or case law) principles.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] It originated in England in the Middle Ages and is the basis for many legal systems around the world.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The courts of England and Wales are headed by the Senior Courts of England and Wales, consisting of the Court of Appeal, the High Court of Justice for civil cases and the Crown Court for criminal cases.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Scots law is a hybrid system based on common-law and civil-law principles.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The chief courts are the Court of Session, for civil cases, and the High Court of Justiciary, for criminal cases.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The Supreme Court of the United Kingdom serves as the highest court of appeal for civil cases under Scots law.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The criminal justice system has been characterised by low conviction rates and court delays for some crime types.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Crime in England and Wales increased between 1981 and 1995.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Since that peak there has been an overall fall of 66% in recorded crime from 1995 to 2015, according to UK crime statistics.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] UK labour laws establish employment rights including a minimum wage, a minimum of 28 days annual holiday, parental leave, statutory sick pay and a pension.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Same-sex marriage has been legal in England, Scotland, and Wales since 2014, and in Northern Ireland since 2020.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] LGBT equality in the United Kingdom is considered advanced by modern standards.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Since leaving the EU most disputes under UK-EU agreements are addressed through consultation between the parties.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] If consultation fails to resolve the issue, either party can request arbitration, typically at the PCA in The Hague.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The EU–UK Trade and Cooperation Agreement states that the UK and EU have to cooperate and negotiate with each other with 'full mutual respect and good faith', as defined by international law.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Under the Windsor Framework, Northern Ireland matters requiring interpretation of EU law go to the ECJ, though the Stormont Brake can prevent new EU rules from taking effect.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The United Kingdom has a highly developed social market economy.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] With an estimated nominal GDP of £2.819 trillion in 2025, it is the fifth-largest national economy in the world and the second-largest in Europe.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Its currency, the pound sterling, is the fourth-most-traded currency in the foreign exchange market and the world's fourth-largest reserve currency, after the United States dollar, the euro and the yen.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The pound sterling maintains its high nominal value through both its long history of stability and by never undergoing formal redenomination.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Since 2022 the UK has been both the world's fourth-largest exporter and fourth-largest importer of goods and services.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Despite having one of the highest levels of income inequality in the OECD, the UK has a very high HDI ranking, including when adjusted for inequality.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] As of 2025 the UK unemployment rate is 4.7% and the annual real GDP per head growth was 1.1%.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] HM Treasury, led by the Chancellor of the Exchequer, is responsible for developing and executing the government's public finance and economic policy.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The Department for Business and Trade is responsible for business, international trade, and enterprise.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The Bank of England is the UK's central bank and responsible for issuing notes and coins in the pound sterling.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Banks in Scotland and Northern Ireland retain the right to issue their own notes, subject to retaining enough Bank of England notes in reserve to cover their issue.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The service sector made up around 80 per cent of the UK's GVA in 2023.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] As of 2023 it is the world's second-largest exporter of services and in 2024 was the world's largest net exporter of financial services.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] London is the world capital for foreign exchange trading, with a market share of 37.8 per cent in 2022 of the global turnover.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] It is the largest urban economy in Europe and, alongside New York, the city in the world most integrated with the global economy.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] London is also one of the world's leading financial centres, ranking second in the 2025 Global Financial Centres Index.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Edinburgh, the UK's second-largest financial centre, ranks 29th in the world in the same index.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The UK's manufacturing sector in 2024 was the world's 10th-largest and Europe's fourth-largest by value output.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] At the end of 2024 manufacturing in the United Kingdom accounted for 8 per cent of the workforce and 8.6 per cent of national economic output.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] As reported in 2017 the East Midlands and West Midlands (at 12.6 and 11.8 per cent respectively) were the regions with the highest proportion of employees in manufacturing.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] London's manufacturing sector had the lowest at 2.8 per cent.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The country's tourism sector is important to the British economy; The creative industries accounted for 5.9 per cent of the UK's GVA in 2019, and contributed £111 billion to the UK economy in 2018.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Lloyd's of London, located in London, is the world's largest insurance and reinsurance market.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] WPP plc is one of the world's biggest advertising companies and also based in London.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The UK is one of Europe's leading retail markets and its largest e-commerce market.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] With consumption expenditures of over US$2 trillion in 2023, it has the second-largest consumer market in Europe.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] John Lewis is the UK's largest employee-owned business.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The British automotive industry generates £47 billion of exports (12 per cent of the UK's total exports of goods).
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In 2024 the UK produced 779,584 passenger vehicles and 125,649 commercial vehicles; 8 out of 10 cars produced in the UK are exported overseas.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Britain is known for iconic cars like Mini and Jaguar, as well as luxury cars such as Rolls-Royce, Bentley and Range Rover.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The UK is a major centre for engine manufacturing: 1.59 million engines were produced in 2024.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] It was the world's third-largest exporter of engines by value in 2023.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The UK motorsport industry has an annual turnover of around £10 billion.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Seven of the eleven Formula One teams are based in the UK, with their technology being used in supercars and hypercars from McLaren, Aston Martin and Lotus.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The aerospace industry of the UK is the second-largest in the world and has an annual turnover of around £30 billion.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The UK space industry was worth £17.5 billion in 2020/21 and employed around 48,800 people.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The UK Space Agency has stated in 2023 that it is investing £1.6 billion in space-related projects.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The British agriculture industry is intensive, highly mechanised and efficient by European standards, producing approximately 60 per cent of the country's overall food requirements and 73 per cent of its indigenous food needs, utilising around 0.9 per cent of the labour force (292,000 workers).
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Around two-thirds of production is devoted to livestock and one-third to arable crops.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The UK retains a significant though much reduced fishing industry, with at least 49 per cent of UK fish sustainably caught in 2020.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The UK marine natural capital assets were estimated to have a value of £211 billion in 2021.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] It is rich in a variety of other natural resources including coal, petroleum, natural gas, tin, limestone, iron ore, salt, clay, chalk, gypsum, lead, and silica and has an abundance of arable land.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] England and Scotland were leading centres of the Scientific Revolution from the 17th century.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The United Kingdom led the Industrial Revolution from the 18th century, and has continued to produce scientists and engineers credited with important advances.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The Department for Science, Innovation and Technology (DSIT) is responsible for helping to develop and manage the UK's scientific, research, and technological outputs.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Scientific research and development remains important in British universities, with many establishing science parks to facilitate production and co-operation with industry.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In 2022, the UK produced 6.0 per cent of the world's scientific research papers and had an 8.8 per cent share of scientific citations, the fourth and third highest among G7 countries and Brazil, China, India, Russia, and South Korea.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The UK ranked 1st among these countries for Field-Weighted Citation Impact.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Scientific journals produced in the UK include publications by the Royal Society, *Nature*, the *British Medical Journal* and *The Lancet*.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] By 2024 the UK tech sector reached a value of US$1.2 trillion surpassing the combined values of the French and German sectors.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Cambridge was named the number one university in the world for producing successful technology founders.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The UK's artificial intelligence industry is the largest in Europe by value and the country ranked fifth globally in a 2026 report on artificial intelligence development by Stanford University.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The UK ranked 6th in the 2025 Global Innovation Index.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In the UK, all traffic drives on the left, with distance and speed being measured in miles, yards and miles per hour (mph).
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] All vehicles manufactured for use in the UK have the steering wheel situated on the right side of the vehicle.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The M25, encircling London, is the largest and busiest bypass in the world.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In 2024 there were 41.7 million licensed vehicles in the UK.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The UK has an extensive railway network of 10,072 miles (16,209 km).
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In Great Britain, the British Rail network was privatised between 1994 and 1997, followed by a rapid rise in passengers.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Great British Railways is a planned state-owned public body that will oversee rail transport in Great Britain.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The UK was ranked eighth amongst national European rail systems in the 2017 European Railway Performance Index assessing intensity of use, quality of service and safety.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] A train runs directly from London to Paris.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Called the Eurostar, it travels through the Channel Tunnel under the English Channel.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] At 23.5 miles long, it is the world's longest undersea tunnel.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] There is also a car service through the tunnel to France called LeShuttle.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The Elizabeth line, a rail link running between East and West London, was named in honour of Queen Elizabeth II in 2016 and opened in 2022.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Another major infrastructure project is High Speed 2 (HS2), a high-speed railway under construction since 2019.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] It will link London with Birmingham, with the potential to extend further north and capable of speeds of up to 225 mph.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In 2023 there were 4 billion bus journeys in the UK, 1.8 billion of which were in London.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The red double-decker bus has entered popular culture as an internationally recognised icon of London and England.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The London bus network is extensive, with over 6,800 scheduled services every weekday carrying about 6 million passengers on over 700 different routes, making it one of the most extensive bus systems in the world and the largest in Europe.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] During 2024 British airports handled nearly 292.5 million passengers.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In that period the three largest airports were London Heathrow Airport (83.9 million passengers), Gatwick Airport (43.2 million passengers) and Manchester Airport (30.8 million passengers).
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] During 2023, 18.3 million passengers travelled internationally by rail and 18.1 million by sea.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In 2021 the UK was the world's 14th-largest consumer and 22nd-largest producer of energy.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] It is home to many large energy companies, including two of the six major oil and gas companies – BP and Shell.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Renewable electricity sources provided 51 per cent of the electricity generated in the UK in 2024.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Wind power was the largest source of electricity in 2024, generating 30 per cent of the UK's total electricity.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The UK has the largest offshore wind farm in the world, which is located off the coast of Yorkshire.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In 2023 the UK had nine nuclear reactors generating about 15 per cent of the UK's electricity.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] There are two reactors under construction and more planned.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In the late 1990s nuclear power plants contributed around 25 per cent of the total annual electricity generation in the UK, but this has gradually declined as old plants have been shut down.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The UK government is investing in small modular reactors that operate via nuclear fission, as well as in research and development towards commercial fusion reactors.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] To that end the government entered into a partnership with the US in late 2023 to collaborate on fusion technology, with "a commercial grid-ready fusion reactor by 2040" stated as a goal.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] At the end of 2023 it was estimated that there were 1.1 billion barrels of oil equivalent of "proven" and "probable" gas reserves and 2.3 billion boe of "proven" and "probable" oil reserves offshore, reducing reliance on imports for energy security and transitioning to renewables.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Emissions from UK gas production are roughly four times lower than imported liquefied natural gas (LNG), according to the UK's oil and gas regulator.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In September 2024 the last coal power station was closed, making coal no longer a power source in the UK.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The UK currently has no fracking (hydraulic fracturing) for shale gas despite a large supply, due to environmental concerns.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Access to improved water supply and sanitation in the UK is universal.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] It was estimated that 96 per cent of households were connected to the sewer network in 2022.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] According to the Environment Agency, total water abstraction for public water supply in the UK was 16,406 megalitres per day in 2007.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In England and Wales, water and sewerage services are provided by 10 private regional water and sewerage companies and 13 mostly smaller private "water only" companies.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In Scotland, said services are provided by a single public company, Scottish Water.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In Northern Ireland, they are also provided by a single public entity, Northern Ireland Water.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Whereas the censuses of England and Wales and of Northern Ireland went ahead as planned in 2021, the census in Scotland was delayed until 2022 due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The Office for National Statistics has estimated that the total population of the United Kingdom recorded in the census would have been 66,912,637 had it been conducted in all parts of the UK on 21 March 2021.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The UK population is the fourth-largest in Europe and the 22nd-largest in the world.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In 2012 and 2013 births contributed the most to population growth, while in 2014 and 2015 net international migration contributed more.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Between 2001 and 2011 the population increased at an average annual rate of 0.7 per cent.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The 2011 census also showed that, over the previous 100 years, the proportion of the population aged 0–14 fell from 31 to 18 per cent, and the proportion of people aged 65 and over rose from 5 to 16 per cent.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In 2018 the median age of the UK population was 41.7 years.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The 2021 census put Scotland's population at 5.48 million, Wales's at 3.1 million and Northern Ireland's at 1.9 million.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] England's population in 2021 was 56 million, representing some 84 per cent of the UK total.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] England is one of the most-densely-populated countries in the world, with 434 people per square kilometre in mid-2021, with a particular concentration in London and the south-east.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] London's wider metropolitan area is the largest in Western Europe, with a population of 14.9 million in 2024.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In 2021 the total fertility rate across the UK was 1.53 children born per woman, which remains considerably below the baby boom peak of 2.95 children per woman in 1964, or the high of 6.02 children born per woman in 1815 and below the replacement rate of 2.1.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In 2011, 47.3 per cent of births in the UK were to unmarried women.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The Office for National Statistics reported in 2015 that amongst the UK population aged 16 and over, 1.7 per cent identify as gay, lesbian, or bisexual (2.0 per cent of males and 1.5 per cent of females); 4.5 per cent of respondents responded with "other", "I don't know", or did not respond.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The number of transgender people in the UK was estimated to be between 65,000 and 300,000 by research between 2001 and 2008.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Historically, indigenous British people were thought to be descended from ethnic groups that settled there before the 12th century: the Celts, Romans, Anglo-Saxons, Norse and the Normans.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Welsh people could be the oldest ethnic group in the UK.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The UK has a history of non-white immigration with Liverpool having the oldest black population in the country dating from at least the 1730s, in addition to having the oldest Chinese community in Europe dating from the 19th century.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In 2021, 83.1 per cent of the UK population was classified as white, 8.6 per cent as Asian or Asian British, 3.7 per cent as Black or Black British, 2.7 per cent as mixed ethnicity, and 2.0 per cent other.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Ethnic diversity varies significantly across the UK.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In 2021, 46.2 per cent of London's population was from a non-white ethnic minority, compared less than 10 per cent in the South West and North East of England, Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The English language is the *de facto* official and most widely spoken language in the United Kingdom.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The UK promotes the language globally to build connections, understanding and trust between people in the UK and countries worldwide.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In the UK, the English language is spoken with distinctive characteristics that collectively form what is known as British English.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The variety of dialects and accents is often noted, with nearby regions frequently having highly distinct variations.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Received Pronunciation is traditionally associated with educated speakers in southern England.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The main national dialects are Scottish English, Welsh English and Northern Irish English.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Distinctive regional varieties include Brummie, Cockney, Geordie, Mancunian, Scouse, West Country, Yorkshire and MLE (Multicultural London English).
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Three indigenous Celtic languages are spoken in the UK: Welsh, Irish and Scottish Gaelic.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Cornish, which became extinct as a first language in the late-18th century, is being revived and has a small group of second-language speakers.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In the 2021 census the Welsh-speaking population of Wales aged three or older was 538,300 (17.8 per cent).
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In addition it is estimated that about 200,000 Welsh-speakers live in England.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In the 2021 census in Northern Ireland 12.4 per cent of people had some Irish language ability and 10.4 per cent had some facility in the Ulster-Scots language.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In 2001, over 92,000 people in Scotland, just under 2 per cent of the population, had some Gaelic language ability, including 72 per cent of those living in the Outer Hebrides.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The number of children being taught either Welsh or Scottish Gaelic is increasing.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Scots, a language descended from early northern Middle English, has limited recognition alongside its regional variant, Ulster Scots in Northern Ireland, without specific commitments to protection and promotion.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] As of April 2020 there are around 151,000 users of British Sign Language (BSL), a sign language used by deaf people, in the UK.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In 2013, it was estimated that 95 per cent of the UK's population were monolingual English speakers.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In 2013, over 5 per cent of the population were estimated to speak languages brought to the UK as a result of immigration.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] South Asian languages are the largest group, which includes Punjabi, Urdu, Bengali, Sylheti, Hindi, Pahari-Pothwari, Tamil and Gujarati.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In the 2011 census Polish was the second-largest language spoken in England, with 546,000 speakers.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In 2019 some three-quarters of a million people spoke little or no English.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Christianity has dominated religious life in the United Kingdom for more than 1,400 years.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Although a majority of citizens still identify with Christianity in surveys, regular church attendance has fallen dramatically since the middle of the 20th century, while immigration and demographic change have contributed to the growth of Islam and other faiths.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] This has led some commentators to describe the UK as a multi-faith, secularised, or post-Christian society.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In the 2021 census of England and Wales, 46.2 per cent of respondents reported that they were Christians, with the next largest faiths being Islam (6.5 per cent), Hinduism (1.7 per cent), Sikhism (0.9 per cent), Buddhism (0.5 per cent), Judaism (0.5 per cent), and all other religions (0.6 per cent).
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Of the respondents, 37.2 per cent stated that they had no religion and a further 6.0 per cent did not answer the optional question.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In the census of Northern Ireland, 42.3 per cent of the population was recorded as Catholic, 37.7% as Protestant or other Christian, 1.3 per cent as belonging to other religions, 17.4 per cent as having no religion and 1.6 per cent did not state a religion.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] A Tearfund survey in 2007 showed that one Briton in ten attends church weekly.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Between the 2001 and 2011 censuses there was a 12 per cent decrease in those who identified as Christian, while the percentage reporting no religious affiliation doubled.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] This contrasted with growth in the other main religious group categories, with the number of Muslims increasing the most to about 5 per cent.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The Church of England is the established church in England.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] It retains representation in the UK Parliament, and the British monarch is its Supreme Governor.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In Scotland the Church of Scotland is the national church.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] It is not subject to state control, and the British monarch is an ordinary member, required to swear an oath to "maintain and preserve the Protestant Religion and Presbyterian Church Government" upon his or her accession.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The Church in Wales was disestablished in 1920 and, because the Church of Ireland was disestablished in 1870 before the partition of Ireland, there is no established church in Northern Ireland.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Although there are no UK-wide data in the 2001 census on adherence to individual Christian denominations, it has been estimated that 62 per cent of Christians are Anglican, 13.5 per cent Catholic, 6 per cent Presbyterian, and 3.4 per cent Methodist, with smaller numbers of other denominations.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Immigration is contributing to a rising population in the United Kingdom, with arrivals and UK-born children of migrants accounting for about half of the population increase between 1991 and 2001.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] According to statistics released in 2015, 27 per cent of UK live births in 2014 were to mothers born outside the UK.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In 2013 approximately 208,000 foreign nationals were naturalised as British citizens, the highest number since 1962.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] This figure fell to around 125,800 in 2014.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Between 2009 and 2013 the average number of British citizenships granted annually was 195,800.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The most common origins of those naturalised in 2024 were Pakistani, Indian, Nigerian, Filipino, Bangladeshi, Italian, Turkish, Romanian and Iranian.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The number of grants of settlement, which confer permanent residence in the UK but not citizenship, was approximately 154,700 in 2013, higher than the previous two years.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Long-term net migration (the number of people immigrating minus the number emigrating) reached a record of 860,000 in 2023, with immigration at 1.326 million and emigration at 466,000.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In comparison, in 2024 net migration was estimated to be 431,000 with immigration at 948,000 and emigration at 517,000.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Emigration was an important feature of British society in the 19th century.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Between 1815 and 1930, around 11.4 million people emigrated from Britain and 7.3 million from Ireland.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Estimates show that by the end of the 20th century, some 300 million people of British and Irish descent were permanently settled around the globe.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In 2006 at least 5.5 million UK-born people lived abroad, mainly in Australia, Spain, the United States and Canada.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Education in the United Kingdom is a devolved matter, with each country having a separate education system.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] About 38 per cent of the United Kingdom population has a university or college degree, the highest percentage in Europe and one of the highest in the world.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The UK is home to many universities, including the University of Oxford and University of Cambridge, which often achieve first place on global rankings.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] University education has varied tuition fees in different regions of the UK.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] England and Wales have a fixed maximum annual fee for all UK citizens, contingent on attaining a certain level of income.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Only those who reach a certain salary threshold pay this fee through general taxation.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Northern Ireland and Scotland have a reduced maximum fee or no fee for citizens where it is their home region.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Some NHS courses have bursaries which pay the fee and in 2017 it was stated that each doctor gets subsidised by £230,000 during their training.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In 2022 the Programme for International Student Assessment (PISA), coordinated by the OECD, ranked the overall knowledge and skills of British 15-year-olds as 14th in the world in reading, mathematics and science.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The average British student scored 494, above the OECD average of 478.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The modern system of universal publicly funded healthcare in the United Kingdom has its origins in the creation of the National Health Service (NHS) in 1949 is the primary healthcare provider in the United Kingdom.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The widespread popularity of the NHS has led to it being described as a "national religion".
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Healthcare in the United Kingdom is a devolved matter and each country has its own system of universal publicly funded healthcare (NHS England, NHS Scotland, Health and Social Care (Northern Ireland) and NHS Wales), although private healthcare is also available.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Public healthcare is provided to all UK permanent residents and is mostly free at the point of need, being paid for from general taxation.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The World Health Organization, in 2000, ranked the provision of healthcare in the United Kingdom as fifteenth-best in Europe and eighteenth in the world.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Since 1979 expenditure on healthcare has increased significantly.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] The 2018 OECD data, which incorporates in health a chunk of what in the UK is classified as social care, has the UK spending £3,121 per person.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] In 2017 the UK spent £2,989 per person on healthcare, near the median for members of the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Regulatory bodies are organised on a UK-wide basis such as the General Medical Council, the Nursing and Midwifery Council and non-governmental-based, such as the Royal Colleges.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p02] Each National Health Service has different policies and priorities.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] The culture of the United Kingdom is influenced by the nation's island status, its history, and being a political union of four countries with each preserving distinctive traditions, customs and symbolism.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] British influence can be observed in the language, culture and legal systems of many of its former colonies, in particular the United States, Australia, Canada, New Zealand and Ireland, a common culture known as the Anglosphere.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Most of its former colonies are Commonwealth countries, bonded by a shared British inheritance.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] A global survey in 2024 ranked the UK third in the 'Most Influential Countries' rankings, behind the US and China.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] British literature includes that associated with the United Kingdom, the Isle of Man and the Channel Islands.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] In 2022, 669 million physical books were sold in the UK, the most ever.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Britain is renowned for children's literature; writers include Daniel Defoe, Rudyard Kipling, Lewis Carroll and Beatrix Potter, who also illustrated her own books.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Tolkien, Roald Dahl, Terry Pratchett and J.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Rowling, who wrote *Harry Potter*, the best-selling book series of all time.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] The playwright and poet William Shakespeare is generally regarded as the greatest dramatist ever and the national poet of England.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Theatre of United Kingdom plays an important part in British culture and has had a vibrant tradition of theatre since the Renaissance with roots going back to the Roman occupation.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Other important figures in the literature of England are Geoffrey Chaucer, known for *The Canterbury Tales*, the poet William Wordsworth, and other Romantic poets, also the novelists Charles Dickens, H.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Wells, George Orwell, Aldous Huxley and Ian Fleming.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] The 20th-century English crime writer Agatha Christie is the best-selling novelist in history.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Twelve of the top 25 of 100 novels by British writers chosen by a BBC poll of global critics were written by women; these included works by George Eliot, Virginia Woolf, Charlotte Brontë, Emily Brontë, Mary Shelley, Jane Austen, Doris Lessing and Zadie Smith.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Scottish literature includes Arthur Conan Doyle (the creator of Sherlock Holmes), Sir Walter Scott, J.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Barrie, Robert Louis Stevenson (whose novel *Treasure Island* strongly influenced the portrayal of pirates in the arts and popular culture), and the poet Robert Burns, who is considered the national poet of Scotland.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] More recently Hugh MacDiarmid and Neil M.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Gunn contributed to the Scottish Renaissance, with grimmer works from Ian Rankin and Iain Banks.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Edinburgh was UNESCO's first worldwide City of Literature.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Welsh literature includes Britain's oldest known poem, *Y Gododdin*, most likely composed in the late 6th century.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] It was written in Cumbric or Old Welsh and contains the earliest known reference to King Arthur.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] The Arthurian legend was further developed by Geoffrey of Monmouth.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Dafydd ap Gwilym (*fl.* 1320–1370) is widely regarded as one of the greatest European poets of his age.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Daniel Owen is credited as the first Welsh-language novelist, publishing *Rhys Lewis* in 1885.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] The best-known of the Anglo-Welsh poets are Dylan Thomas and R.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Thomas, the latter nominated for the Nobel Prize in Literature in 1996.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Leading Welsh novelists of the twentieth century include Richard Llewellyn and Kate Roberts.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Northern Ireland's most popular writer is C.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Lewis, who was born in Belfast and wrote *The Chronicles of Narnia*.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Irish writers, living at a time when all of Ireland was part of the United Kingdom, include Oscar Wilde, Bram Stoker (who wrote *Dracula*) and George Bernard Shaw.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] There have been many authors whose origins were from outside the United Kingdom but who moved to the UK, including Joseph Conrad, T.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Eliot, Kazuo Ishiguro, Sir Salman Rushdie and Ezra Pound.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] The United Kingdom is famous for "British Empiricism", a branch of the philosophy that states that only knowledge verified by experience is valid, and 'Scottish Philosophy', sometimes referred to as the 'Scottish School of Common Sense'.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] The most famous philosophers of British Empiricism are John Locke, George Berkeley and David Hume; while Dugald Stewart, Thomas Reid and William Hamilton were major exponents of the Scottish "common sense" school.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Two Britons are also notable for the ethical theory of utilitarianism, a moral philosophy first used by Jeremy Bentham and later by John Stuart Mill in his short work *Utilitarianism*.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] The BBC, founded in 1922, is the United Kingdom's publicly funded radio, television and Internet broadcasting corporation, and is the oldest and largest broadcaster in the world.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] It operates television and radio stations across the UK and abroad and its domestic services are funded by the television licence.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] The BBC World Service is an international broadcaster owned and operated by the BBC, and the world's largest.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] It broadcasts radio news, speech and discussions in more than 40 languages.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Other major players in the UK media include ITV, which operates 11 of the 15 regional television broadcasters that make up the ITV Network, and Sky.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Newspapers produced in the United Kingdom include the *Daily Mail*, *The Guardian*, *The Telegraph*, *The Times*, and the *Financial Times*.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Magazines and journals published in the United Kingdom that have achieved worldwide circulation include *The Spectator*, *The Economist*, *New Statesman* and *Radio Times*.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] London dominates the media sector in the UK: national newspapers and television and radio are largely based there, although MediaCityUK in Manchester is also a significant national media centre.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Edinburgh and Glasgow, and Cardiff, are important centres of newspaper and broadcasting production in Scotland and Wales, respectively.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] The UK publishing sector, including books, directories and databases, journals, magazines and business media, newspapers and news agencies, has a combined turnover of around £20 billion and employs 167,000 people.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] In 2015 the UK published 2,710 book titles per million inhabitants, more than any other country, with much of this exported to other Anglophone countries.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] In 2010, 82.5 per cent of the UK population were Internet users, the highest proportion amongst the 20 countries with the largest total number of users in that year.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] The British video game industry is the largest in Europe, and since 2022 the UK has the largest video game market in Europe by sales, surpassing Germany.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] It is the world's third-largest producer of video games after Japan and the United States.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Major British artists include the Romantic artists William Blake, John Constable, Samuel Palmer, and J.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Turner; the portrait painters Sir Joshua Reynolds and Lucian Freud; the landscape artists Thomas Gainsborough and L.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] The Royal Academy in London is a key organisation for the promotion of the visual arts in the United Kingdom.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] The Courtauld Institute of Art is a leading centre for the teaching of the history of art.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Important art galleries in the United Kingdom include the National Gallery, National Portrait Gallery, Tate Britain, and Tate Modern (the most-visited modern art gallery in the world, with around 4.7 million visitors per year).
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Various styles of music have become popular in the UK, including the folk music of England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] English folk features melodic ballads with strong lyrics and music for country dancing often using accordion and fiddles.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Scottish folk features bagpipes and fiddles playing traditional dance tunes with bouncy tempos.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Welsh folk has harps and vocal harmonies often sung in Welsh.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Northern Irish folk blends fiddles with flutes merging Scottish and Irish influences.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Historically, there has been Renaissance music from the Tudor period, with masses, madrigals and lute music by Thomas Tallis, John Taverner, William Byrd, Orlando Gibbons and John Dowland.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] After the Stuart Restoration, an English tradition of dramatic masques, anthems and airs became established, led by Henry Purcell, followed by Thomas Arne and others.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] George Frideric Handel composed the anthem *Zadok the Priest* for the coronation of George II; it became the traditional ceremonial music for anointing all future monarchs.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Handel's many oratorios, such as his famous *Messiah*, were written in English.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] In the second half of the 19th century, Arthur Sullivan and his librettist W.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Gilbert wrote their popular Savoy operas, and Edward Elgar composed a wide range of music.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Increasingly, composers became inspired by the English countryside and its folk music, notably Gustav Holst, Ralph Vaughan Williams and Benjamin Britten, a pioneer of modern British opera.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Amongst the many post-war composers, some of the most notable have made their own personal choice of musical identity: Peter Maxwell Davies (Orkney), Harrison Birtwistle (mythological), and John Tavener (religious).
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Recent classical singers include Alfie Boe, Bryn Terfel, Katherine Jenkins, Michael Ball, Roderick Williams, Russell Watson and Sarah Brightman, while Nicola Benedetti and Nigel Kennedy are renowned for their violin ability.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] According to *The New Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians* the term "pop music" originated in Britain in the mid-1950s to describe rock and roll's fusion with the "new youth music".
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] *The Oxford Dictionary of Music* states that artists such as the Beatles and the Rolling Stones drove pop music to the forefront of popular music in the early 1960s.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Birmingham became known as the birthplace of heavy metal, with the band Black Sabbath starting there in the 1960s.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] In the following years, Britain took part in the development of rock music, with British acts pioneering hard rock, raga rock, heavy metal, space rock, glam rock, Gothic rock, psychedelic rock and punk rock.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] British acts also developed neo soul and created dubstep.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] The UK has produced some of the most prominent English-speaking rappers along with the United States, including Stormzy, Kano, Yxng Bane, Ramz, Little Simz and Skepta.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] The Beatles have international sales of over 1 billion units and are the biggest-selling band, in addition to being widely regarded as the most influential band in the history of popular music.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Other prominent British contributors to popular music over the last 50 years include the Rolling Stones, Pink Floyd, Queen, Led Zeppelin, the Bee Gees and Elton John, all of whom have worldwide record sales of 200 million or more.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] The Brit Awards are the BPI's annual music awards, and some of the British recipients of the Outstanding Contribution to Music award include the Who, David Bowie, Eric Clapton, Rod Stewart, the Police and Fleetwood Mac (who are a British-American band).
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] More recent UK music acts that have had international success include George Michael, Oasis, Spice Girls, Radiohead, Coldplay, Arctic Monkeys, Robbie Williams, Amy Winehouse, Susan Boyle, Adele, Ed Sheeran, Lewis Capaldi, One Direction, Harry Styles and Dua Lipa.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] As of 2024 the UK is the world's third-largest music market behind the US and Japan, and in 2021 was the second-largest exporter of music behind the US.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Many British cities are known for their music.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Acts from Liverpool have had 54 UK chart number 1 hit singles, more per capita than any other city worldwide.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Glasgow's contribution was recognised in 2008 when it was named a City of Music by UNESCO.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Manchester played a role in the spread of dance music such as acid house, and from the mid-1990s, Britpop.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] London and Bristol are closely associated with the origins of electronic music sub-genres such as drum and bass and trip hop.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] UK dance music traces its roots back to the black British Sound System Culture and the New Age Traveller movement of the 60s and 70s, it also has influences from the Chicago House and Detroit Techno scenes.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] In the late 80's, dance music exploded with Rave culture mainly Acid House tracks which were made mainstream with novelty records (such as Smart E's Sesame's Treet and the Prodigy's Charly) and the Balearic sound brought back from the Ibiza club scene.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] This led on to genres such as UK Garage, Speed Garage, Drum and bass, Jungle, Trance, and Dubstep.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Influential UK dance acts past and present include 808 State, Orbital, the Prodigy, Underworld, Roni Size, Leftfield, Massive Attack, Groove Armada, Fatboy Slim, Faithless, Basement Jaxx, Chemical Brothers, Disclosure, Calvin Harris, and Fred Again.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Other influential UK DJs include Judge Jules, Pete Tong, Carl Cox, Paul Oakenfold, John Digweed and Sasha.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] The United Kingdom has had a considerable influence on the history of the cinema.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] The British directors Alfred Hitchcock, whose film *Vertigo* is considered by some critics as the best film of all time, and David Lean, who directed *Lawrence of Arabia*, are amongst the most critically acclaimed directors ever.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Recent popular directors include Christopher Nolan, Sam Mendes, Steve McQueen, Richard Curtis, Danny Boyle, Tony Scott and Ridley Scott.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Many British actors have achieved international fame and critical success.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Some of the most commercially successful films have been produced in the United Kingdom, including two of the highest-grossing film franchises (*Harry Potter* and *James Bond*).
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] 2019 was a particularly good year for British films which grossed around £10.3 billion globally, accounting for 28.7 per cent of global box office revenue.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] UK box-office takings totalled £1.25 billion in 2019, with around 176 million admissions.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] In 2023 UK film and television studio stage space stood at 6.9 million sq ft, with 1 million sq ft added in the past year with more in development.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] The annual BAFTA Film Awards are hosted by the British Academy of Film and Television Arts.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] British cuisine developed from influences reflective of its land, settlements, arrivals of new settlers and immigrants, trade and colonialism.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] The food of England has historically been characterised by simplicity of approach and a reliance on the high quality of natural produce.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] The traditional Sunday roast is one example, featuring a roast joint (usually of beef), lamb, chicken, or pork, often free range (and generally grass-fed, in the case of beef).
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Roasts are served with either roasted or boiled vegetables, Yorkshire pudding and gravy.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] Other traditional meals include meat pies and stews.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] A poll by YouGov in 2019 rated classic British food, with more than 80 per cent liking the Sunday roast, Yorkshire pudding, fish and chips, crumpets and the full English breakfast.
[src:united-kingdom/united-kingdom-p03] The UK is home to a large selection of fine dining.
